INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (1, 2, 'Government', 9.0, 'Access to clean water is undeniably one of the most fundamental human rights. As water is essential for survival, many argue that it should be provided free of charge to every household. While I acknowledge the importance of access to clean water, I believe that while it should be a priority, providing it entirely for free might not be the most sustainable solution. This essay will explore both sides of the argument.\nOn the one hand, clean water is essential for the well-being of every individual. It is crucial not only for drinking but also for sanitation, hygiene, and the overall health of populations. In many developing countries, people suffer from waterborne diseases due to a lack of clean water. If clean water were provided free of charge, it could significantly reduce health risks and contribute to better living conditions, especially in poverty-stricken areas where people struggle to afford basic necessities. Governments would ensure that every citizen has access to water, and this would align with the principle that water is a basic human right, available to all.', NULL, NULL, 'Access to clean water is undeniably one of the most fundamental human rights. As water is essential for survival, many argue that it should be provided free of charge to every household. While I acknowledge the importance of access to clean water, I believe that while it should be a priority, providing it entirely for free might not be the most sustainable solution. This essay will explore both sides of the argument.\nOn the one hand, clean water is essential for the well-being of every individual. It is crucial not only for drinking but also for sanitation, hygiene, and the overall health of populations. In many developing countries, people suffer from waterborne diseases due to a lack of clean water. If clean water were provided free of charge, it could significantly reduce health risks and contribute to better living conditions, especially in poverty-stricken areas where people struggle to afford basic necessities. Governments would ensure that every citizen has access to water, and this would align with the principle that water is a basic human right, available to all.\nHowever, providing water free of charge to everyone could lead to some challenges. One of the major concerns is sustainability. The cost of water infrastructure, such as treatment plants, pipelines, and maintenance, is high. If water is given for free, governments would need to find ways to fund these operations. This might result in higher taxes or reallocation of resources from other essential sectors such as healthcare or education. Moreover, the free provision of water might encourage wasteful consumption. When people do not pay for something, they may use it carelessly, leading to wastage and strain on available water resources. In some regions, overuse of water can result in environmental damage, such as depletion of water supplies or contamination of fresh water sources.\nIn conclusion, while I strongly believe that access to clean water is a human right, I do not fully support the idea of providing water free of charge to all households. Instead, governments should consider subsidizing water costs for low-income households and focus on promoting water conservation, ensuring both accessibility and sustainability.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (2, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'In many countries, primary and secondary schools close for two months or more during the summer holidays. In this essay, I will explore the value of long school holidays and the reasons why shorter breaks may be beneficial.\nOne significant advantage of long school holidays is that they allow students to relax and recharge. After months of studying, children and teenagers often experience stress and fatigue. A lengthy break gives them the opportunity to rest, engage in leisure activities, and spend time with their families. This can have a positive impact on their mental health and well-being. Additionally, long holidays can offer students a chance to explore other interests and hobbies that they might not have time for during the school year. For example, many students take part in summer camps, learn new skills, or travel, all of which contribute to their personal development.', NULL, NULL, 'In many countries, primary and secondary schools close for two months or more during the summer holidays. In this essay, I will explore the value of long school holidays and the reasons why shorter breaks may be beneficial.\nOne significant advantage of long school holidays is that they allow students to relax and recharge. After months of studying, children and teenagers often experience stress and fatigue. A lengthy break gives them the opportunity to rest, engage in leisure activities, and spend time with their families. This can have a positive impact on their mental health and well-being. Additionally, long holidays can offer students a chance to explore other interests and hobbies that they might not have time for during the school year. For example, many students take part in summer camps, learn new skills, or travel, all of which contribute to their personal development.\nHowever, there are also strong arguments in favor of shorter school holidays. One key reason is that shorter breaks can help maintain students\' academic progress. With longer holidays, students may forget what they have learned and spend significant time catching up when school resumes. This can lead to a lack of continuity in their learning, especially for younger students. Furthermore, long holidays may create a gap in socialization, as students are not interacting with their peers or teachers for extended periods. Shorter breaks would ensure that students stay engaged with their education while still providing time for rest and recreation.\nIn conclusion, while long school holidays offer valuable opportunities for rest, personal growth, and family bonding, the benefits of shorter breaks should not be overlooked.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (3, 2, 'Environment', 9.0, 'Many people nowadays have decided to stop flying or limit the number of times they use this form of transport. While this could undoubtedly bring significant benefits to the environment, it may result in higher expenses for individuals and businesses. I believe that the disadvantages for individuals and businesses would outweigh the environmental benefits. This essay will discuss both the advantages and disadvantages of reducing air travel.\nThe environmental benefits of reduced air travel would directly impact the amount of pollution in the air, leading to a greener planet. However, this reduction in air travel could also lead to an increase in the use of other forms of transportation, such as cars, buses, or trucks. For example, if the number of vehicles on the road increases, this could also lead to higher levels of greenhouse gas emissions.', NULL, NULL, 'Many people nowadays have decided to stop flying or limit the number of times they use this form of transport. While this could undoubtedly bring significant benefits to the environment, it may result in higher expenses for individuals and businesses. I believe that the disadvantages for individuals and businesses would outweigh the environmental benefits. This essay will discuss both the advantages and disadvantages of reducing air travel.\nThe environmental benefits of reduced air travel would directly impact the amount of pollution in the air, leading to a greener planet. However, this reduction in air travel could also lead to an increase in the use of other forms of transportation, such as cars, buses, or trucks. For example, if the number of vehicles on the road increases, this could also lead to higher levels of greenhouse gas emissions.\nOn the other hand, for individuals and businesses, this change could result in higher travel costs, as well as longer journeys and potential delays in reaching destinations. These factors can negatively affect companies\' resources and, in some cases, may result in the loss of business deals or prevent new ones from being initiated due to limited trading times. Higher travel costs could also lead companies to cut jobs, which would have devastating consequences for families.\nIn conclusion, I believe that the disadvantages for individuals and businesses caused by reduced air travel are far greater. The potential consequences for companies, such as increased travel and shipping costs, could result in financial losses and job cuts. Although the environmental benefits are important, they may not justify such a drastic cultural shift, and other pollutants could rise as a result of increased use of alternative forms of transport.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (4, 2, 'Culture', 9.0, 'In today’s interconnected world, global fashion trends have a significant impact on the way people dress. With the advent of social media, international influencers, and the rapid spread of information, fashion has become a global phenomenon. This essay will explore the reasons behind the rise of global fashion and discuss whether this trend has a positive or negative impact on society.\nOne major factor contributing to the dominance of global fashion is the widespread use of social media platforms. Through websites like Instagram, TikTok, and Pinterest, fashion trends can spread rapidly across borders. Fashion influencers, celebrities, and designers use these platforms to showcase new styles, which are often quickly adopted by millions of people worldwide. This constant exposure to global trends influences individuals\' clothing choices, making it more likely that people will dress in similar styles regardless of their geographical location.', NULL, NULL, 'In today’s interconnected world, global fashion trends have a significant impact on the way people dress. With the advent of social media, international influencers, and the rapid spread of information, fashion has become a global phenomenon. This essay will explore the reasons behind the rise of global fashion and discuss whether this trend has a positive or negative impact on society.\nOne major factor contributing to the dominance of global fashion is the widespread use of social media platforms. Through websites like Instagram, TikTok, and Pinterest, fashion trends can spread rapidly across borders. Fashion influencers, celebrities, and designers use these platforms to showcase new styles, which are often quickly adopted by millions of people worldwide. This constant exposure to global trends influences individuals\' clothing choices, making it more likely that people will dress in similar styles regardless of their geographical location.\nAnother contributing factor is the growth of global brands and the ease of international shopping. Today, it is easier than ever for people to purchase clothing from any part of the world, thanks to online shopping and global delivery services. International brands like Zara, H&M, and Gucci are now household names in many countries, and their collections often set the tone for the latest fashion trends. The availability of these brands across the globe has created a more unified global fashion culture, where people are more likely to wear similar styles and brands, regardless of where they live.\nWhile global fashion has created a sense of unity and allowed for self-expression, I believe this trend has both positive and negative consequences. On the positive side, it has democratized fashion, making it accessible to people from various backgrounds. It has also allowed for the exchange of cultural styles, promoting diversity in fashion. However, the negative aspect is that global fashion can contribute to the loss of cultural identity. As people increasingly wear the same clothing, there is a risk that traditional dress codes and local fashion styles may be overshadowed or forgotten. Additionally, the constant pressure to follow global trends can lead to over-consumption and waste, as people feel the need to buy new clothes frequently to keep up with the latest trends.\nIn conclusion, global fashion has become a major influence on how people dress due to the power of social media and the global reach of fashion brands. While this has led to greater accessibility and diversity in fashion, it has also caused concerns over the loss of cultural identity and environmental sustainability.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (5, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'In modern society, the role of competition and cooperation in our work, school, and daily life often creates a topic of discussion. Some individuals argue that competition is beneficial, while others believe that we should focus more on teamwork and cooperation.\nThose in favor of competition contend that it is a powerful motivator, encouraging people to', NULL, NULL, 'In modern society, the role of competition and cooperation in our work, school, and daily life often creates a topic of discussion. Some individuals argue that competition is beneficial, while others believe that we should focus more on teamwork and cooperation.\nThose in favor of competition contend that it is a powerful motivator, encouraging people to\nstrive for excellence\nand achievement. For instance, in an educational context, competition might push students to study harder to receive a top grade, thus improving overall academic performance. The same principles apply in the workplace. Employees, eager to excel, may work harder and more efficiently, thereby increasing productivity and driving their\ncareer advancement\n. In this regard, competition proves to be a catalyst for personal improvement and organizational success.\nOn the other hand, supporters of cooperation argue that it\nfosters\na\ncollaborative spirit\n, leading to collective success. In schools, group projects promote the development of important life skills such as teamwork, communication, and problem-solving abilities. Unlike competition, cooperation builds empathy, as students learn to understand and appreciate diverse perspectives. In workplaces, teamwork often leads to innovative solutions since multiple minds generate a variety of ideas leading to more efficient and creative problem-solving.\nIn my opinion, a balance between competition and cooperation is the optimal approach. While competition motivates individuals and fosters a culture of achievement, too much competition can create an environment of stress and potentially stifle creativity. Similarly, while cooperation is essential for mutual growth, a lack of competitiveness might create a sense of complacency.\nIn conclusion, as competitive and collective forces both have their unique benefits, an efficient blend of both approaches can bring about individual and communal progress.\nCultivating\nthis balance allows people to\nthrive\npersonally and professionally, contributing to overall societal development.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (6, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Views on reducing the workweek and extending weekends provoke contrasting opinions. I support this concept, as I believe it\nenhances productivity', NULL, NULL, 'Views on reducing the workweek and extending weekends provoke contrasting opinions. I support this concept, as I believe it\nenhances productivity\n, health, and\nwork-life balance\n.\nHigh productivity levels may be achieved by reducing the duration of the work week. Often, productivity is inversely proportional to the number of hours worked, indicating that continuous work with minimal pauses can lead to diminished returns. Fewer workdays focused on intensive tasks and two additional days for\nrelaxation and recuperation\ncould enhance overall performance. Some businesses have experimented with this strategy, witnessing an overall rise in productivity.\nThe health benefits derived from a shorter workweek and longer weekends are notable. Long work hours often transport people into a quagmire of stress, leading to ailments like insomnia, obesity, cardiovascular diseases, and more. An extended weekend provides space for physical exercise, leisure activities, or spending quality time with loved ones, contributing positively to mental and physical well-being.\nDespite the clear benefits, implementing a shorter workweek requires meticulous planning and management. Employers need to\nmaintain a high work standard\nand ensure all projects are duly completed within the given time frame. To some, fewer work hours might equate to less business. However, various case studies have shown improved financial returns and happier workforces in companies who have dared to adopt\nflexible time structures\n.\nIn essence, reducing the workweek and elongating the weekend would indeed be a\nmonumental shift\nin the\nprofessional landscape\n. Still, considering the potential benefits in worker productivity, health, and work-life balance, it is a proposition worth considering.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (7, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'The concept of saving money, often regarded as an\nessential endeavor', NULL, NULL, 'The concept of saving money, often regarded as an\nessential endeavor\nfor adults, is also being emphasized for younger generations today. I wholeheartedly agree with the notion that saving is a\ncrucial habit\nto develop early in life for\nfinancial security\n, cultivating discipline, and\npromoting independence\n.\nMost importantly, having savings provides a critical cushion for unexpected life events. Life is full of uncertainty, including sudden health issues or unexpected job losses. Having a substantial amount saved can help\nmanage\nsuch unexpected circumstances\nwith\nmore\nease\n. This importance can be underscored by promoting the idea of saving amongst the young to prepare them for the unpredictability that life has to offer.\nMoreover, young people who are encouraged to save from a tender age tend to grow into disciplined adults. They develop the ability to set priorities, distinguishing between needs and wants, and making informed decisions on their spending. These skills then help in their daily lives, making them financially aware and savvy.\nPromoting saving among young people not only helps them become independent early but also opens a plethora of opportunities for them. With savings, a college student may be able to\nchip away at\ntheir education loan early, put a down payment on a car, or pursue a business idea or other entrepreneurial pursuits. This self-sufficiency and the opportunities it provides are invaluable supports for young people\'s\npersonal and professional development.\nUnderstandably, some may argue that young people should live in the moment and delay saving for the future. While enjoying youth is important, it should not be at the expense of preparing for the future.\nIn conclusion, the practice of saving money is critical for everyone. While it may seem challenging to young people who are beginning to navigate their financial lives, the long-term benefits—ranging from financial security to disciplined decision making—certainly outweigh the inconvenience.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (8, 2, 'Urbanization & Globalization', 9.0, 'The advent of globalisation has undeniably impacted various facets of life, one prime example being the ubiquitous availability of international foods in local supermarkets. In my opinion, while this progression brings with it several positive attributes such as\ncultural exchange', NULL, NULL, 'The advent of globalisation has undeniably impacted various facets of life, one prime example being the ubiquitous availability of international foods in local supermarkets. In my opinion, while this progression brings with it several positive attributes such as\ncultural exchange\nand variety, it also carries significant drawbacks related to environmental concerns and local agriculture.\nOne distinct advantage of this development is the introduction of cultural diversity through food. In today\'s global village, consumers can conveniently experience foreign cuisines through their regional supermarkets. For instance, an individual in Britain can easily sample Asian flavours like soy sauce or exotic Indian spices without having to travel overseas. Consequently, this exposes individuals to various cultures, fostering multicultural understanding and acceptance.\nMoreover, the global accessibility of food complements our modern lifestyle by readily providing us with out-of-season produce. Illustratively, residents in harsh winter regions can enjoy summer fruits like watermelon and mango due to this international food trade. This luxury of choice was previously unimaginable and is hence considered a positive outcome of globalisation.\nHowever, this global food trade also poses severe threats to our environment. Food transportation across vast distances contributes significantly to\ncarbon emissions\n, augmenting the\nclimate crisis\n. For instance, the extensive air freighting of asparagus from Peru to markets in Europe has detrimental environmental repercussions.\nFurthermore, the predominance of global food might\nundermine\nlocal farmers. Often, imported goods are priced competitively, leaving local producers struggling to compete. This can jeopardize their livelihood and potentially lead to the extinction of local varieties. For instance, in Nepal, imported Indian rice is often cheaper than native varieties, leading to a decline in local rice cultivation.\nIn conclusion, while there are undeniable benefits of global food availability such as enhanced cultural understanding and improved food variety, significant negatives such as environmental damage and threats to local agriculture cannot be overlooked. Therefore, making informed,\nenvironmentally-friendly decisions\nwhile taking advantage of the global food marketplace seems to be an\noptimal approach\n.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (9, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'The pace of scientific development is swift, yet not all advances appear beneficial to society. Occasionally, even the creators of such innovations harbor regrets about their inventions. This essay\ncontends', NULL, NULL, 'The pace of scientific development is swift, yet not all advances appear beneficial to society. Occasionally, even the creators of such innovations harbor regrets about their inventions. This essay\ncontends\nthat while science should not inflict harm, the pursuit of knowledge and the betterment of human lives should be of equal importance to scientists.\nThere is a compelling case to be made for prioritizing the public good as the foremost objective for scientists. Their unique position enables them to make discoveries and\ndevise\ninventions that have the capacity to transform society. The advent of electricity, advancements in modern medicine, breakthroughs in telecommunications, and the emergence of the internet\nexemplify\nthe types of scientific progress that have substantially improved the human condition.\nConversely, there are instances where scientists\nembark on\nresearch primarily to expand their own understanding. It is imperative that their work is\nconducted harmlessly\n, yet the eventual applications of their findings and their impact on societal improvement often remain unknown until the research concludes. For example, Alfred Nobel created dynamite with the intention of aiding mining operations, unaware that it would later\nbe utilized in\nweaponry. Similarly, the discovery of penicillin, a monumental life-saving antibiotic,\nwas serendipitous\n.\nIn summary, it is clear that the enhancement of human life should\nbe a central aim\nof science. Nonetheless, the pursuit of knowledge and the act of discovery\nare intrinsically valuable\ngoals for scientists and are essential to the progression of science. It is frequently the case that the full implications and uses of scientific discoveries are not realized until after the work has reached its fruition.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (10, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'In the realm of higher education, a debate exists regarding the breadth versus depth of learning. Some students\nadvocate for', NULL, NULL, 'In the realm of higher education, a debate exists regarding the breadth versus depth of learning. Some students\nadvocate for\na diversified educational approach, exploring subjects beyond their major disciplines, while others\nemphasize\nthe importance of concentrated studies within their chosen field to enhance professional qualifications.\nThose in favor of a broad-based education argue that exposure to a variety of subjects\nfosters\na well-rounded intellect, enhancing critical thinking and adaptability. This approach could potentially lead to a more comprehensive understanding of the world, as different disciplines offer unique perspectives and problem-solving strategies. For instance, a computer science student might benefit from studying psychology to better understand user behavior, or a business student could\ngain insights\nfrom history to comprehend economic cycles.\nOn the contrary, proponents of specialized study insist that mastery of a subject is vital in today’s competitive job market. They contend that delving deeply into a field equips students with advanced knowledge and skills, thus increasing employability and expertise. A medical student, for example,\ndedicating\nall their time\nto\nmedicine, is likely to have a stronger grasp of complex medical issues than one who\nsplits their focus\n.\nIn my view, a balanced approach is\noptimal\n. While specialization is important for career development, interdisciplinary knowledge can lead to innovation and a more agile mind. The synergy between understanding one\'s main subject in depth and appreciating the insights from other fields can\nyield\na holistic and more effective education.\nUltimately, universities should encourage students to pursue their main subjects with vigor while also offering opportunities to explore interdisciplinary courses. This dual approach prepares students not only for specific careers but also for the challenges of a dynamic and interconnected world.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (11, 2, 'Urbanization & Globalization', 9.0, 'Statistics indicate\na rapid increase', NULL, NULL, 'Statistics indicate\na rapid increase\nin the global population, with projections suggesting that the majority of individuals will reside in urban areas within the coming decades. The debate surrounding whether urbanization constitutes a positive or negative phenomenon remains contentious.\nThe swift migration of people from rural to urban regions inevitably\ntriggers challenges\n. Primarily, it\nexacerbates pressure\non vital resources such as housing and transportation. Affording suitable housing in cities has become increasingly arduous for many individuals, consequently\ngiving rise to\nthe emergence of slums, where low-income families conglomerate in neglected urban areas. Unfortunately, these communities often find themselves ensnared in a cycle of poverty that proves challenging to break free from.\nFurthermore, the expansion of urban areas contributes to severe\ntraffic congestion\nas a growing number of vehicles commute from the suburbs to the city center. This\nengenders\nnumerous\nripple effects\n, including issues concerning air quality and mental health concerns among urban residents who grapple with the stress and exhaustion of navigating through sprawling cities.\nHowever, despite these challenges, I contend that urbanization is not entirely detrimental. Well-managed large cities offer\na plethora of advantages\n. They provide increased educational opportunities due to the availability of more schools and offer superior access to healthcare services. Additionally, some cities have implemented innovative solutions such as ride-sharing programs, e-bikes, and park-and-ride services, which mitigate environmental problems associated with urbanization.\nIn my view, while many of the issues linked with urbanization are preventable, addressing the burgeoning populations in cities poses\na formidable challenge\n. The strategies employed by governments, businesses, and society to confront this challenge will significantly shape the trajectory of our world\'s future.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (12, 2, 'Government', 9.0, 'In numerous regions globally, a noticeable demographic trend is the aging of populations, attributed to\nextended lifespans', NULL, NULL, 'In numerous regions globally, a noticeable demographic trend is the aging of populations, attributed to\nextended lifespans\nand\ndeclining birth rates\n. This shift presents a multitude of advantages and disadvantages, yet this essay posits that, overall, the benefits of an older population outweigh the drawbacks.\nA primary concern stemming from an aging populace is the financial burden it\nentails\n. With longer life expectancy, individuals may require financial support for over three decades during retirement, either from governmental assistance or familial resources. Additionally,\nage-related illnesses\nstrain healthcare systems, diverting resources from addressing broader societal needs. Furthermore, the financial independence of older generations can exacerbate challenges for\nyounger cohorts\n, such as\nheightened\ncompetition for housing and employment opportunities.\nNevertheless, it is crucial to acknowledge the substantial contributions older individuals make in terms of wisdom, experience, and skill sets. Many seniors remain active and productive well into their later years, serving as valuable assets to the economy and society. They continue to contribute\npost-retirement\nthrough various means, including charitable endeavors, consumer spending, and family support. Additionally, the involvement of grandparents in childcare facilitates the participation of both parents in the workforce, enhancing\noverall economic productivity\n.\nDespite the challenges posed by an aging population, the significant societal benefits brought forth by elderly individuals outweigh these concerns. Their invaluable contributions enrich communities, economies, and\nfamilial structures\n, emphasizing the importance of embracing and supporting an aging populace. While governments may face challenges in adapting to\ndemographic shifts\n, the enduring benefits seniors bring to society make them an invaluable asset deserving of recognition and support.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (13, 2, 'Abstract', 9.0, 'It is said that taking risks brings a lot of benefits. However, it also gives us some\ndrawbacks', NULL, NULL, 'It is said that taking risks brings a lot of benefits. However, it also gives us some\ndrawbacks\n.\nFirst of all, it is obvious that taking risks will\ncause a great loss\nif people do it and fail. In personal\nlife, this loss might not be so harmful. However, it will be really harmfull in professional life,\nbecause people take a responsibility not only for themselves but also others such as colleages,\ncustomers and their families. It will even damage the society from the\neconomic point\n.\nOn the other hand, we can receive huge benefits by taking risks. Firstly, we can learn how to\nprepare for one goal through this process. In order to achieve the aim, people will make all the\nefforts to think about it and try to find more efficient way. If they do this in the\nprofessional\ncircumstances\n, they will recognise the responsibility and importance of cooperation.\nAlso, it will be completely meaningful even though people can’t achieve the goal after taking risks.\nThey will learn the reason why they have failed and how to change it. The failure will enable them to\nimprove their skills and to\nachieve their object\nnext time.\nAs I mentioned, it is true that taking risks give us both advantages and disadvantages. However, it\ncan be argued that the benefits outweighed the drawbacks in that we can obtain advantages not only\nfrom the result but also from the process of taking risks.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (14, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Mobile phones nowadays\ncontain essential features', NULL, NULL, 'Mobile phones nowadays\ncontain essential features\nfor entertainment as well. There has been a significant increase in the usage hours of smartphones among youngsters. Several reasons contribute to this situation, and I find this development more beneficial than negative. Both the reasons and my views are\nelaborated\nfurther.\nThe first reason for the overuse of smart devices by youngsters is the social benefits they provide. The smartphone, connected to the internet,\nopens up large possibilities\n, from creating new friends to communicating with them through social media. For instance, a child in my neighborhood chats for hours with his school friends on Facebook (a social media platform) and spends time on online video-sharing phone applications. Moreover, mobile gaming, especially multiplayer games, is another major reason for this situation. Children play different kinds of games on their phones for entertainment purposes and immerse themselves in the games in such a way that they forget about the time and other responsibilities.\nHowever, I believe that smartphones have also increased the knowledge of students. They have developed important social skills, such as communication skills, teamwork, and more, by allowing them to work and play in groups without the restriction of distance. Additionally, children can learn through the internet by watching online videos and reading articles, ultimately helping them in their studies as well as language skills. For example, whenever my niece needs to know about something, she searches for it on the internet and learns from it. Moreover, multiplayer online gaming\nimproves their multitasking ability\nand provides a competitive environment.\nOverall, I agree that the overuse of smartphones\non a regular basis\nis harmful to them, but with proper guidance, mobile phones can help them learn some lifelong skills.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (15, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'As the number of professionals working abroad increases, there is often debate over whether they should remain in the country where they received their training or if they should be free to move to another country if they wish to do so. While I believe that individuals should be free to migrate, I also acknowledge that it can have negative effects on the country where they were trained.\nOn the one hand, professionals who decide to work abroad are in search of a different lifestyle and career opportunities. They should be permitted to', NULL, NULL, 'As the number of professionals working abroad increases, there is often debate over whether they should remain in the country where they received their training or if they should be free to move to another country if they wish to do so. While I believe that individuals should be free to migrate, I also acknowledge that it can have negative effects on the country where they were trained.\nOn the one hand, professionals who decide to work abroad are in search of a different lifestyle and career opportunities. They should be permitted to\nenhance their lives\nbeyond the constraints of\ntheir country of origin. For example, while in Spain, residents in a hospital may not have hands-on experience due to safety measures, in other countries, such as Argentina, residents actively practice their skills with patients. Moreover,\ncultural exchanges\nhave been shown to increase efficiency, as different nationalities introduce new beliefs and methods.\nOn the other hand, when professionals leave the country where they were trained, it can cause social and economic harm. In countries where the government provides free education and healthcare, many people believe that the population should repay the country with their skills and knowledge. Additionally, a study on South African emigration has highlighted that when a professional leaves the country, it can result in the loss of 10 unskilled jobs. Therefore, it affects the economy and the community.\nTaking everything into account\n, it can be said that relocating from the country of training should not be taken lightly, considering the\nadverse effects\non the population. However, I am firmly convinced that an individual’s professional development should not be restricted by their country of origin, and professionals should be allowed to seek better opportunities abroad.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (16, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Since ancient times, people have sought to heal themselves using herbs and other natural products. In modern times, this approach is referred to as alternative medicine. Nowadays, an increasing number of people with various ailments are\nchoosing', NULL, NULL, 'Since ancient times, people have sought to heal themselves using herbs and other natural products. In modern times, this approach is referred to as alternative medicine. Nowadays, an increasing number of people with various ailments are\nchoosing\nalternative medicine\nover\nconventional medical treatments. In this essay, I will discuss the\npros and cons\n.\nIn my view, the disadvantages of using traditional medicine\noutweigh the advantages\n. The\nprimary concern\nis the uncertainty surrounding how these treatments will affect an individual\'s health. Numerous cases have been reported where herbal remedies triggered allergic reactions, resulting in fatalities. Another issue is that individuals without medical training often experiment with alternative medicines. They are unaware of the potential outcomes and optimistically hope for positive results, which are not always guaranteed.\nDespite these drawbacks, certain advantages persuade some people to bypass conventional medical practitioners. The foremost benefit is that using herbs does not contribute to environmental issues such as air pollution or chemical waste. Many pharmaceutical companies utilize substances that adversely affect the environment. Another advantage is the\ncost-effectiveness\nof alternative medicines; they are often much more affordable than conventional treatments, as there is no need to purchase expensive medications from pharmacies.\nIn conclusion, alternative treatments will always have a place because they offer benefits that some people believe can outweigh the negatives. However, I disagree. I believe that conventional medicine, which is advancing rapidly, will eventually eclipse other forms of treatment in the future.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (17, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'There\nemerges', NULL, NULL, 'There\nemerges\na common phenomenon that more dwellers in some countries show growing interests in exploring the history of their residence. This tendency is determined by various factors and several approaches to supporting the process of research will be suggested later.\nTwo main reasons have contributed to this change of public attitude. The improvement of people\'s living quality can be a fundamental reason. If they struggled with their basic needs for living security, residents would not be eager to study their properties, neither the history. It is, therefore, reasonable to understand that more people in developed countries rather than developing ones are attempting to do so. The other determinant is the\nprevalence of\narchitectural history advocated by mass media. Among various channels,\ndocumentary series\nplay a key role in introducing and educating the public about the housing history, especially in some regions with a rich heritage of historical resources. People in such places are more motivated to\nexcavate\nthe previous records in order to learn more about their inhabitance.\nUnlike scientists or scholars, those local residents may not specialize in researching what has happened to their houses, but there still remain some possible methods for better understanding. The most effective approach might rely on the internet, which provides\nan enormous amount o\nf information about buildings and houses wherever they are. That means people can directly search what they want to know on their smartphones or laptops by just typing in the name of a place, after which related stories are presented immediately. In addition, fieldwork investigations can also be implemented if the older generation in local area is available. By visiting and interviewing those elderly inhabitants, people may get access to first-hand information that is more reliable and authentic.\nIn conclusion, the historical background of living is attractive to some people as a result of improved living\ncondition and influences from the media, and they can research on their own with the help of the Internet\nand local residents.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (18, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'Nowadays, many companies market their products by putting stress on the updates to some degree. This widely implemented advertising strategy results from two main reasons and I personally consider this an improvement in the business world.\nThere are primarily two factors contributing to the', NULL, NULL, 'Nowadays, many companies market their products by putting stress on the updates to some degree. This widely implemented advertising strategy results from two main reasons and I personally consider this an improvement in the business world.\nThere are primarily two factors contributing to the\nemphasis\non new products in some organizations. The first one is that something new is usually more attractive to consumers because the nature of humans is to be curious. By\ndrawing public attention\n, producers might\nearn more revenues\nby selling more products, which is consistent with the\nprofit-oriented goal\nof most organizations. Another point is that innovation has become a universal notion in business strategies, by which competitive companies are forced to develop and renew their products on a regular basis. That is why we can see many slogans and advertisements publicizing new products that are available or coming soon.\nIn regard to this business trend, it can exert more positive effects to both customers and manufacturers. For consumers, it is favorable to purchase the latest products because people can\nperceive unique feelings\nfrom those novelties. An instance is that the launch of new smartphones and electronic products by Apple Inc. has become a spotlight in high-tech industry annually. It is particularly attractive to younger consumers who pursue to own those new devices with distinguished styles and functions. In this way, they are possible to receive the sense of satisfaction and distinction derived from those updates. Not only consumers, but also manufactures can benefit from newly-launched products: In addition to high returns earned from those goods, better\nbrand images\nmight be built if businesses constantly update new items. That is because these sellers are able to impress their potential and existing customers by showing progressive technology and pursuit.\nIn conclusion, taking novelty as a marketing technique is arguably a beneficial development to both-side partners in business.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (19, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Today high levels of sugar are contained in many sources of food, especially in manufactured food. And, of course, eating so much sugar is not good for our health: it can cause just a simple cavy, for example, but also worse problems, like the increasing level of sugar in blood. Some people suggest that sugary products should be more expensive, so people would buy less of them.\nAccording to me, I think that this solution is not the best one as', NULL, NULL, 'Today high levels of sugar are contained in many sources of food, especially in manufactured food. And, of course, eating so much sugar is not good for our health: it can cause just a simple cavy, for example, but also worse problems, like the increasing level of sugar in blood. Some people suggest that sugary products should be more expensive, so people would buy less of them.\nAccording to me, I think that this solution is not the best one as\nsugary products\ninclude some types of food that we eat everyday, such as bread or pasta. This foods, particularly the first one, are really important in our diet, so make them more expensive will influence not only our lifestyle, but also some people wouldn\'t be able anymore to buy the most important food for them. Just think for example to poor people, who can maybe afford a few loads of bread per day: what would they eat if we increased bread price?\nI think that the best solution for this problem would be informing people about what they eat, because sometimes we don\'t even know that. They have already done something to inform people about\nthe characteristics of food\n, of course, and lebels are one of the most important thing, as they tell you all the ingredients of a particular food. Yet, not many people spend some of their time reading lebels, or, if they do it, they probably don\'t know the biggest part of the substances named in the list, as well not everybody knows that there is a\nspecific order of the ingredients\nin the list. So something we could do is organizing some \"talks\" to inform people not only about the function of labels, but especially about the big amount of sugar we eat everyday. I think as well that this talks should be organised also in schools, because also children must be aware of what they eat; besides, children can tell what they have learned by these \"conferences\" at their parents, so the whole family would eat better.\nTo sum it up, I think that it is not necessary to increase the prices of sugary food and that all we need is information, that will lead people to eat less sugary food and,\nas a consequence\n, live better with less problems.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (20, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'Some people believe that drivers are likely to be unnecessary because of the advanced self-driving technology in the future. In my point of view, this will\nexert more negative impacts', NULL, NULL, 'Some people believe that drivers are likely to be unnecessary because of the advanced self-driving technology in the future. In my point of view, this will\nexert more negative impacts\non people and the society.\nIt cannot be denied that the popularization of driverless automobiles could\nbring a series of noteworthy benefits\n. The most significant one might be the decrease of traffic accident rate thanks to the\ncutting-edge technology\n, which provides high-precision automatic driving system for all vehicles, thereby the frequent accident resulting from fatigue and drunk driving could be largely eliminated. The stress of people derived from long-time driving could also be relieved as they no longer need to drive by themselves, which means that people, especially those who used to be drivers, are able to enjoy the short or long road trips with leisure activities, such as reading books.\nHowever, this might bring more negative effects on the public and the society. For one thing, drivers of buses, underground and trucks would suffer unemployment, if they were unable to get a new job. The living standard of them and their families would, to some extent, be affected. For another, as all of the vehicles running on the roads are managed by the central control centre,\ntraffic congestion\nor even accidents in a city would occur due to system failure in this centre. Long-term dependence on automatic driving may lead to a result that the vast majority of passengers are\nincapable of\nstarting the engine and driving by themselves. Under such circumstances, all that they can do is to wait for the resetting of the system, which decreases efficiency and causes considerable inconvenience.\nTo conclude, driverless automobiles could benefit the users in many ways indeed. However, if those cars should fully replace the traditional vehicles, the above-mentioned adverse impacts would emerge.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (21, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'In some countries the ownership of peoples\' home is an important matter. In these countries it is very important to own your own home rather than renting it. It might be indifferent for some, but for these people it matter.\nWhy is that the case? you might wonder. I think it is because your home is supposed to be exactly what it', NULL, NULL, 'In some countries the ownership of peoples\' home is an important matter. In these countries it is very important to own your own home rather than renting it. It might be indifferent for some, but for these people it matter.\nWhy is that the case? you might wonder. I think it is because your home is supposed to be exactly what it\nsounds like, your home. As a human I think we long after having stuff to\ncall our own\n, doesn\'t matter what it is, but humans will always want to claim ownership. This is nothing new and it has been like this through human history, like colonies for example, which later once again became the same country as before lead by its own inhabitants. People will always want to be the one to decide what happens to them and when you rent your home you can\'t even paint it without the owners permission.\nIf you as a person are renting an apartment there might be a lot of stressors in your life. A scratched wall can cause you a major headache, because the wall was not yours. The bedroom you are currently sleeping in might not be available as long as you hope, things happen in life and maybe the next landlord won\'t want to have you as a tenant. In other perspective, not owning your home could be a relief\nwhen it comes to\nyour finance. As a renter you won\'t have to pay mortgage, take loans or spend an awful lot of money on buying the property. You wouldn\'t have to worry about the house market crashing or a natural disaster destroying your expensive home.\nBottom line\n, as a human I feel like we need to have a home and calling it your own can make that more special. I personally would rather own my house, because then whatever happens it is on me and no one else.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (22, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'Some people argue that paper books are not needed afterward as a result of the wide application of online reading. Personally, I\npartially agree', NULL, NULL, 'Some people argue that paper books are not needed afterward as a result of the wide application of online reading. Personally, I\npartially agree\nwith this statement.\nUndeniably\n, massive materials available on the internet can benefit certain groups. For example, people with a fast pace of life may find it less efficient to spend time in the library searching specific books. Instead, with the help of the internet, those people are able to read what they want straightway, by which they can save extra time for other affairs. Apart from that, it is also beneficial to most readers with lower income because the reading costs can be greatly deducted. On considering that most paper journals are unaffordable because of its publishing and transporting, those people suffering from\nliving expenditure\nmight prefer online reading with lower prices.\nHowever, it is unreasonable to assume that printed readings are no longer popular because they are\nirreplaceable\nto the elderly and students. For those senior people, reading paper newspapers and books is more consistent with their traditional lifestyle than searching online. If they are provided with an e-reader, they might feel frustrated because of the\ninability in\nusing electronic devices. That can explain why there are still many public libraries and large book malls which are prepared for those traditional readers. In addition to older group, youngsters are also supposed to read more physical books because in that way they can be more concentrated on learning itself. That is because young students are most likely to be distracted by online temptations, which include cyber games, subscribed messages and attractive TV series. By noticing these annoying information, young people may pay less attention on reading journals and fail to study productively.\nIn conclusion, although online reading is more economic in time and cost, traditional printed books are still\nvaluable because of its advantages.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (23, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'Advertisement has always been a\ncrucial part', NULL, NULL, 'Advertisement has always been a\ncrucial part\nin the world of marketing. Throughout the decade, we have seen a significant increase in the amount of advertisements, whether it is on the media like television or widespread through social network platforms. The goal of advertisements is to get consumers to buy a targeted product, and while this method has been proven\nconsiderably\nsuccessful generally, some people view it as too prevalent to catch the consumers\' attention any more.\nAdvertisements can act as a strong persuasion device to seemingly\nhypnotize\npeople\ninto\nbuying goods and services. This is so because of the tactics placed in the messages, such as showing people having a good time together when using a particular product, using bandwagen, showing only the upsides of usage, and applying compare and contrast strategies to show the effects of using the product and make it stand out. Even if people do not know it, these messages are repeated several times and soon it may brainwash people to Finally go out and get the product. For instance, if a person is watching television and sees a certain advertisement of a snack many times, the repeated sight of the scrumptious food may result in that person feeling hungry and succumbing to the advertisement at last.\nNevertheless, there is another point of view in which the widespread of advertisements makes it a normal thing. After watching a dozen of advertisements people will see it as a mere every day routine and cease to pay attention to the message of the advertisement. Some people may even choose to turn off a television channel, for instance, only just to avoid seeing and hearing repetetive advertisements. After a certain frequency, they start to get bored and stop paying attention to ads. Hence, in the end, the main goal of advertisements is not complete since the people whom the messages are sent out to do not receive that message. A real life example can be seen from advertisements in a particular social media platform, Youtube. In the Youtube\nmarketing mechanism\n, advertisements are place before and in between videos, hoping that the viewers would also be forced to watch the advertisements, too. However, this is not\nusually the case, since many people would just click \"Skip Ad\" and continue on.\nIn conclusion, advertisements can be successful in persuading people to purchase goods and services, or they can be unsuccessful in many ways. They are very commonly seen nowadays, but not all of them\nfulfill their purpose\n. Thus, advertisements must be designed and presented in the correct way to result in the highest effectiveness.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (24, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'In some cultures, in order to encourage children to achieve more, parents usually\nimbue', NULL, NULL, 'In some cultures, in order to encourage children to achieve more, parents usually\nimbue\nan idea to the young generation that persistent efforts can lead to success. In my point of view, this kind of educational thought may not be inappropriate in many cases.\nSometimes children can benefit from this notion. Firstly, encouragement from parents and teachers is beneficial to\nboost children\'s confidence\n. For example, when they\nsuffer from some setbacks\nin learning, they may get bored with study.\nParental trust and encouragement can help them to regain motivation, so that they are willing to work hard on their lessons and their efforts might be rewarded in the end. In addition, sufficient encouragement can help children to pluck up the courage to try something new, which they are afraid of, such as swimming. They may start to take an interest in doing this after the first attempt.\nHowever, the foregoing parenting method undoubtedly has many disadvantages to children as well. First and foremost, children may be misled when\nstriving for\ntheir career development. It is acknowledged that almost all of the outstanding basketball players have the great advantage of being tall. They cannot realize their dreams if they do not have this feature, even though significant efforts are made. Besides, this kind of indoctrination has adverse influences in the\ncultivation of children\'s characters\n. Children who grow up with too much encouragement are likely to be overconfident, which leads to\nan unclear perception\nof themselves and the outside world. Further, they may set unrealistic targets that are impossible to achieve, and this may finally cause the breakdown mentally.\nIn general, it is unnecessary for parents to urge their kids to achieve anything. Young children should be taught to\nestablish a practical outlook on life\n.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (25, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Some people believe that it is best to accept a bad situation, such as an unsatisfactory job or shortage of money. Others argue that it is better to try and improve such situations.\nBased on my knowledge, some people choose to accept the fate that they have to', NULL, NULL, 'Some people believe that it is best to accept a bad situation, such as an unsatisfactory job or shortage of money. Others argue that it is better to try and improve such situations.\nBased on my knowledge, some people choose to accept the fate that they have to\nundergo\nthe bad situation as they believe that good things might come out of it. Their solution is simply to just\ngo with the flow\nbecause they think that they will learn something new along the journey. For example, a student received a grade B for his Physics examination. However, he only needs one more mark to get an A. If a student requires to receive a mark percentage of 70% to get an A, this student got a 69% on his paper. As the teacher looked through the questions with the whole class, he notices that the teacher accidentally marked his correct answer to wrong. So, realistically, he should get an A. However, he chooses to leave his grade as a B because he believes that his current grade will be a motivation for him to improve and work harder to get a better grade in the next examination. Hence, this explains why some people chooses to accept the bad situation.\nBesides that, it is also mentioned that others argue that is better to try and improve such situations. I believe the reason they act that way is because they feel a bit paranoid that the situation will become worse if they do not do so. For instance, a person had to undergo a shortage of money. Logically, they will feel a little\nparanoid\nthat at one point, they might have to experience an empty pocket and had to live in the streets. Regarding that matter, they figured out a solution to\nimprovise\nsuch situations by getting an extra or part-time job. This solution will help them to gain extra money to pay their daily expenses such as water and electricity bills. This means that their problems are solved and they are now worry-free. In my honest opinion, I strongly suggest that one can choose to act in both situations according to situations. When facing a problem, think of the best solution to solve it. If the situation requires you to simply ignore it, then just do so. There is a no need in figuring out a way to improve those situations as it will take up your time and cause stress. However, if the situation requires you to take action quickly, by all means do so as you might not know what are the consequences if you ignore the problem.\nIn a conclusion, the main important thing when facing bad situations is to analyze the problem, then only you can react to them. Not all bad situations needs to be ignored and not all needs to be improved. Think wisely to get the best solution for all of your problems.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (26, 2, 'Environment', 9.0, 'Some people consider that the loss of individual species of plants and animals is the main environmental problem of our time. Attempts to preserve rare or dying species are carried out in zoos or other specialist plant and animal facilities, through breeding programmes, preservation orders and other forms of protection and there was genuine sadness among many when the last surviving white rhino died earlier this year.\nSurvival of the fittest is nature\'s way of ruthlessly allowing weaker specimens to', NULL, NULL, 'Some people consider that the loss of individual species of plants and animals is the main environmental problem of our time. Attempts to preserve rare or dying species are carried out in zoos or other specialist plant and animal facilities, through breeding programmes, preservation orders and other forms of protection and there was genuine sadness among many when the last surviving white rhino died earlier this year.\nSurvival of the fittest is nature\'s way of ruthlessly allowing weaker specimens to\ndie out\n, although mankind\nhas also contributed to falling animal numbers through hunting and poaching. However, whether saving individual species should be the main focus of environmental protection is debatable. Climate change and excessive use of plastic are just two other major problems that deserve our attention.\nThe evidence of climate change is there for us all to see: rising sea levels and associated flooding with the loss of homes at low land levels are becoming more frequent. Many countries and island communities are now\ncalling for urgent action\nto delay,\nhalt or even reverse the process\n, although if we believe the experts, reversal is impossible. Habitable areas are gradually shrinking, often for some of the poorest groups of people, but there seems to be little obvious action taking place. If the major contributors to climate change will not support the reduction of greenhouse gases, there is little hope for the future.\nNaturalists have also begun to expose the serious problems arising from discarded plastic waste. Birds and animals can die\ngruesome\ndeaths through being trapped or caught up in plastic bags or ropes, while the long process required for these plastics to decay means that they remain a threat for many years to come. Worse, there is now beginning to be evidence of sea creatures ingesting smaller globules of\ndisintegrating\nplastic, which harms them and all the other creatures in their particular food chain.\nThe loss of particular species, both flora and fauna, is cause for regret, but I do not agree that they are the most important environmental problems these days. If climate change and damage from plastic continue, there will be less land and less food for everyone, including plants and animals.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (27, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Music is one of the most popular art forms, with a common belief that it is a bridge to connect people of different cultures and ages. I completely agree with this opinion.\nMusic is thought of as a universal language. Initially, although people cannot', NULL, NULL, 'Music is one of the most popular art forms, with a common belief that it is a bridge to connect people of different cultures and ages. I completely agree with this opinion.\nMusic is thought of as a universal language. Initially, although people cannot\ncomprehend\nthe lyrics of\nforeign songs,\nthe rhythm of\nthese songs could be appreciated by them. It is widely known that American Rock and Korean pop music are popular among different cultures. Fans of these music from all over the world are willing to discuss their favourite pop stars and songs on social media. This makes people of different cultures share common topics. Some of them even become friends. Besides, nowadays, it is quite common for celebrated bands or singers to take world concert tours so that fans from different regions can experience the same feast of music.\nIn addition, it is a common knowledge that the musical preferences of older generations\ndiffer considerably from\nthat of the youth. However, it is not surprising to find that young adults are fond of the classical music as there is no boundary of age in the world of music. Likewise, some seniors are fanatical fans of rock music that is mainly produced for the young. The senior rock fans may also attend some music festivals, during which they can sing and dance together with many young people. Furthermore, some parents, whose children are adolescents and not willing to communicate with them, could discuss the pop music and singers with them. The family could also go to the concert together so that they could be much closer.\nIn conclusion, music is a kind of language shared by people of different cultures, generations, and nations. Therefore, I do agree that music can not only bring people together but is also one of the most\ncrucial\ncommunication tools among countries.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (28, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Most contemporary economies allow such a model of employment as being self-employed, which appears very tempting for many. However, still the vast majority of people opt for being employed in a company and not to set up their own business. This essay will attempt to look into the key factors as to why people may prefer entrepreneurship and\nmajor drawbacks', NULL, NULL, 'Most contemporary economies allow such a model of employment as being self-employed, which appears very tempting for many. However, still the vast majority of people opt for being employed in a company and not to set up their own business. This essay will attempt to look into the key factors as to why people may prefer entrepreneurship and\nmajor drawbacks\nto it.\nTo start with, in many modern societies, including Russian, entrepreneurship is greatly encouraged with lots of business seminars and workshops advertised. These may range from slightly fraudulent to\ngenuinely educational\nand supportive, and generally any information on setting up a company is easily accessible for those who are willing. And willing they are, as being a business person, the image itself has a certain feel of luxury, respectability and success. People are being told that they have no limits and can easily become as wealthy as a Steve Jobs is they wish it.\nThis first reason is linked to the second, which is relevant for Russia and some other counties. Bank loans are accessible too, and they are largely eagerly granted. If a future business person truly knows their business, it\nposes no threat\n. Nevertheless, easy access to setting up a company for someone inexperienced or insensible may cause a range of problems.\nApparently, the first issue that may perplex an unskilled entrepreneur is the necessity to be a jack of all trades (if the company is very small). Having taken the responsibilities of an accountant, PR or HR manager at the same time can be a burden and make the person wish they had never done it at all. If they hire other people to perform these tasks, they must pay more tax and provide their employees with decent working conditions. At the same time, business is usually a risky matter and in our competitive reality many of them go bankrupt. And last, but not least- self-employed people are the only people responsible for their own vacations, sick or maternity leaves or any job perks.\nSo,\nin a nutshell\n, being your own master has many downsides, that is why many people decide to play it safe.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (29, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'International immigration is an increasingly common phenomenon in some regions. Those residents are therefore required to speak a different language from their mother tongue to adjust their lives to a different cultural context, which may cause some problems. From my view, I agree with this statement to a large extent.\nA new foreign language may bring various challenges to immigrants in terms of social and practical perspectives. Initially, the ineffective communication caused by language barriers might', NULL, NULL, 'International immigration is an increasingly common phenomenon in some regions. Those residents are therefore required to speak a different language from their mother tongue to adjust their lives to a different cultural context, which may cause some problems. From my view, I agree with this statement to a large extent.\nA new foreign language may bring various challenges to immigrants in terms of social and practical perspectives. Initially, the ineffective communication caused by language barriers might\nbe detrimental to\nsocial life. That is to say, when people cannot express themselves correctly, it may lead to conflicts in a community. More seriously, the participants who hold different opinions might fight or behave violently, which is likely to create criminal cases.\nIn addition to social issues, foreign residents might\nencounter\npractical problems in their daily life, especially for those who are in employment. A common phenomenon is that new employees who have moved from other countries might be more familiar with their mother tongue. When\nsettling in a new environment\nwith different communicating media, immigrant employees might encounter\ncommunication pitfalls\ncaused by language barriers, which may cause misunderstanding and inefficiency in their workplace.\nAlthough people might meet the above challenges when living abroad, it would be especially beneficial for some children who study in foreign countries to become bilinguals. Compared with those students who have never been abroad, the children who are immersed in a foreign environment for a long time are more likely to master a second language unconsciously.\nTo conclude, living in a foreign country may cause serious problems related to social conflicts and working inefficiency despite of the benefit that it\ncultivates\nbilingual talents.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (30, 2, 'Abstract', 9.0, 'The answer is complex since there are a lot of choices in our life and all of them are different kinds. In some cases I would say that it is a good thing to have the ability to choose from a wide variety. Take for example gastronomy. Every single person has different meals on their list of favourites. Actually if you have a bigger family it is almost impossible to cook something that everyone would like. Therefore I would say that it is great that you can go to a shopping center and choose from a dozen different food types. I can always find something that looks delicious.\nNaturally, there are some people who say that it is against', NULL, NULL, 'The answer is complex since there are a lot of choices in our life and all of them are different kinds. In some cases I would say that it is a good thing to have the ability to choose from a wide variety. Take for example gastronomy. Every single person has different meals on their list of favourites. Actually if you have a bigger family it is almost impossible to cook something that everyone would like. Therefore I would say that it is great that you can go to a shopping center and choose from a dozen different food types. I can always find something that looks delicious.\nNaturally, there are some people who say that it is against\nevolution\n. They claim to say that back in the old days we had a perfect life when technically everybody was farming. I personally disagree with that. I am happy that I could choose a job that\nfits best to my abilities\n. I mean no one is the same, why would we want to do the same? Different kinds of universities give us the opportunity to beome who we are\nmeant to be\n. We have the right to choose.\nHowever there is one topic where, according to my opinion, we have too many choices. This specific area is television. There are hundreds of channels, therefore you can always find something that is worth watching. Literally you could sit in your sofa the whole day and watch films. I think that people doing less outdoor activities are the results of the many available channels. From this point of view I would agree that we have too many choices.\nIn conclusion I would say that we can\'t generally talk about choices since they could be different. In some cases it is good to have many of them while in other areas they could have a negative effect.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (31, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Both History and Science and Technology are key components of the school syllabus. It is controversial whether History is more important than Science and Technology. From my own perspective, nowadays,studying Science and Technology can contribute more to students\' development.\nAdmittedly, history has its irreplaceable impacts on schooling. First and foremost, learning history is beneficial to', NULL, NULL, 'Both History and Science and Technology are key components of the school syllabus. It is controversial whether History is more important than Science and Technology. From my own perspective, nowadays,studying Science and Technology can contribute more to students\' development.\nAdmittedly, history has its irreplaceable impacts on schooling. First and foremost, learning history is beneficial to\nenrich students knowledge\nin many ways, including politics, economics, culture and international relations. They are able to be more knowledgeable about study and life by accumulating those information in history classes. Besides, learning the historical events and figures of their own countries can help students to have a better understanding of their nations and\nbuild a sense of patriotic duty\n. If students learned about the impressive stories of national heroes that died for the interest of their country, they would\ncherish the life they own\nmuch more.\nHowever, the skills learned from science and technology could be more conducive to the future of students. Firstly, science and technology, as dominant engines of the rapid development of the modern society, continually create thousands of related jobs, such as software engineers, User Interface designers and data analysts. The graduates who have acquired more expertise in these fields are more competitive to get those jobs and possibly have better\ncareer prospects\n. In addition, compared with historical knowledge that is more academic, science and technology are more practical, which means that they are more helpful in people\'s daily lives. For example, the invention of smart washing machine and other intelligent household appliances can help people to save time in doing housework.\nAs far as I am concerned, although both subjects mentioned above should be added to the school curriculum, the students who have mastered Science and Technology could be more adaptable to the rapid change of society.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (32, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Although the advancement in the field of agriculture technology has\npromoted the production', NULL, NULL, 'Although the advancement in the field of agriculture technology has\npromoted the production\nof crops, famine is still a severe problem that needs to be solved urgently in some areas.\nThe adverse geographical factors, including the lack of irrigation water and extreme climate, or more specifically, the imbalance between farmland and population result in the shortage of grain supply. Taking Africa as an example, the grain output in this area is a far cry from meeting the basic food demands of local residents because of the harsh natural environment, including the shortage of rainfall and the soaring population. Further, the high international trade tariffs make the imported food unaffordable for the poor, such as wheat, soybean and rice. Besides the above causes, these years, the irrational human activities have led to the wide\nenvironment depredation\nand the consequent natural disasters, including droughts and floods. All of these disasters will bring a reduction to the harvest.\nFacing the pressing issue, some effective means need to be adopted. Initially, measures of improving the natural environment should be taken as a\npriority\n, such as\nthe prohibition on deforestation\n. These measures will relieve the pressure of forest degradation and soil erosion which lead to the low yield of local produce. Meanwhile, governments should play a key role in managing market factors to lower the unaffordable price so that the poor are able to buy food. For instance, the trade tariffs of grains and crops need to be reduced. Those policies will be beneficial for developing countries to import agricultural produce from other nations.\nIn conclusion, sufficient food is one of the basic needs of human beings, and people from all walks of life are responsible for improving\nthe status quo\n.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (33, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'Due to the advancement in technology, information explosion becomes a distinctive feature for this era. Some people\nadvocate', NULL, NULL, 'Due to the advancement in technology, information explosion becomes a distinctive feature for this era. Some people\nadvocate\nthat all nations should share what they know about in significant fields, while others go against the exchange of valuable information. In my view, it is beneficial to share much information for world peace.\nAdmittedly, it is believed that some information is of great value so that it should not be shared without any returns. For instance, the research results cannot be gained until domestic scientists pay hard efforts for a long time. If this scientific information is disclosed to other nations, the enthusiasm of these scientists might be\ndispelled\n. More seriously, they may become uninspired on science and fail to\nundertake\nfuture researches.\nHowever, more countries will benefit from the open sharing of information with each other in terms of medical progress. That means people are more likely to live a longer life with fewer sufferings using joint wisdom. Taking the coronavirus epidemic as an example, if governments do not cooperate with each other by contributing their latest findings on this disease, the entire human race will face an\nunprecedented\ncrisis, brought by the mortality and other humanitarian disasters heightened by the pandemic.\nIn my opinion, countries should share what they have discovered as much as possible aiming at global peace and stability. If those developed countries can share more scientific resources with other countries, they will\nestablish closer relations\nwith the developing ones. By helping each other, international relationships might be improved and the conflicts leading to regional or even world wars might be avoided.\nTherefore, the global environment will become more peaceful with fewer national wars. In conclusion, I am more supportive of the view that nations should share information if they expect a more friendly global environment.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (34, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'The age structure of a country is one of the main research subjects for demographers. Nowadays, there is an increasing trend that the population is becoming younger, which is regarded as more advantaged to both economy and households.\nAdmittedly, the loss of traditional culture might result from the growing number of younger people. Compared with older people who are more likely to', NULL, NULL, 'The age structure of a country is one of the main research subjects for demographers. Nowadays, there is an increasing trend that the population is becoming younger, which is regarded as more advantaged to both economy and households.\nAdmittedly, the loss of traditional culture might result from the growing number of younger people. Compared with older people who are more likely to\ninherit\ntraditions such as unique handicrafts or extinct languages, younger people are less possible to do such things. That means younger generations are less able to preserve those traditions by applying them into daily life. It is because the youth are growing up in the environment where technology and information are advanced but traditional customs are rarely seen. Therefore, they might perceive those treasure from ancestors as old fashions, which is a risk to reserve\ntraditions.\nHowever, more youngsters in a society may\ncontribute to\nthe great economic growth. It is a fact that the majority of the workforce is young adults who are more advantaged in their physical condition. Therefore, they might work in a longer shift compared with older employees. Furthermore, younger consumers are more likely to purchase a wide range of products from both online and physical stores. Those enthusiastic customers are easily persuaded to spend money due to fancy advertisements and celebrity endorsements, by which the economy might\nprosper\n.\nIn addition, more young people means that there are more younger labours to\ngenerate fortune\nfor the society, while the elderly are usually to be taken care of with medical treatment and healthcare by the government. In a worse situation, their pension may not be enough to cover the expenditure on medicine and treatment, so the larger amount of medical expenditure have to\nbe shouldered by\nother family members, which would be a heavy financial burden on the most middle-class or low-income households.\nIn conclusion, there are more benefits than drawbacks if a nation\'s age structure leans heavily on the younger generation.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (35, 2, 'Government', 9.0, 'The allocation of government funds to transportation\ninfrastructure is a', NULL, NULL, 'The allocation of government funds to transportation\ninfrastructure is a\ncontentious issue\n. While some argue that investing\nin high-speed intercity rail networks is crucial, others contend that\nupgrading existing public transport systems should take priority. This\nessay will examine both perspectives before concluding that a balanced\napproach is optimal.\nProponents of high-speed railways\nemphasize their potential to boost economic growth and connectivity. By\ndrastically reducing\ntravel time between major cities, these trains can\nfacilitate\nbusiness exchanges, tourism, and regional integration. For\ninstance, Japan’s Shinkansen and France’s TGV have demonstrated how\nefficient rail systems can stimulate economic activity while offering an\neco-friendlier alternative\nto air travel.\nConversely, advocates for improving existing public transport\nargue that urban populations benefit more from reliable buses, subways,\nand trams. Many cities face\nchronic issues\nlike overcrowding, delays,\nand\ninadequate accessibility\n—problems that directly affect low-income\ncommuters. Allocating funds to maintain and expand these services would\nenhance daily mobility for millions. For example, expanding London’s\nUnderground or New York’s subway lines would\nalleviate congestion\nmore\neffectively than a high-speed train linking distant cities.\nAdditionally, maintaining current systems is typically less costly than\nbuilding new\ninfrastructure from scratch.\nIn my view, governments should\nstrike a balance\nbetween the two approaches.\nHigh-speed rail is valuable for long-term national development, but\nneglecting local public transport exacerbates inequality and\ninefficiency.\nA pragmatic solution\nwould be to prioritize urgent urban\nupgrades while gradually investing in intercity projects where demand is\nproven. For instance, revenue generated from improved city transport\ncould later subsidize regional rail initiatives.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (36, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Life habits formed in childhood could, to a large extent, shape his or her character. Some people encourage their children to make decisions about daily matters of themselves while others\nhold no brief for', NULL, NULL, 'Life habits formed in childhood could, to a large extent, shape his or her character. Some people encourage their children to make decisions about daily matters of themselves while others\nhold no brief for\nthis opinion. From my perspective, I\nam in favour of\nthe former.\nOn the one hand, the educational notion of giving children the freedom to make choices for their daily life might impact on children\'s personalities and even the whole society negatively. Young children who grew up with this way of life are likely to be self-serving. For example, when eating out, they usually\nprioritize\nthe dishes that they like, without considering others preference. Although parents are willing to\nmeet their demands\n, such behaviour might\narouse discontent\nwith people around them. Thus, it might be hard for them to\nintegrate into\nsociety. Further, the whole society can hardly be integrated and harmonious with a multitude of people who are self-centred.\nHowever, some people believe that the young generation needs to be the decision makers of themselves. This concept might be based on the importance of cultivating independence of them since childhood. More specifically, a child with the over-protection from their family members would probably be over-dependent, so that he or she is unable to be a strong-minded person who can make essential choices in adult life.\nIn my point of view, giving the freedom of making their own choices to the offspring could be conducive to shaping their character as well as being independent individuals in the aspects of emotion, thinking and living. But it does not mean that young children can ignore others\' preferences and feelings. Therefore, parents should not only provide some privileges to their children but also teach them to be more observant of others\' feelings, helping them to become mature and sociable adults.\nIn conclusion, children should be allowed to choose what they prefer while some restrictions of their behaviour are also necessary.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (37, 2, 'Government', 9.0, 'In recent decades, most countries have developed their economies by\nimproving transportation', NULL, NULL, 'In recent decades, most countries have developed their economies by\nimproving transportation\n, which mainly includes railways and roads. I partially agree with the view that governments should invest money on railways instead of roads. Instead, I believe the investment should be balanced, because both of them are significant infrastructure, exerting a big influence on life and the economy.\nInitially, it is necessary for nations to\ndevelop road conditions\nbecause road construction has a certain influence on residents\' commuting. In many cities, commuters are used to travel to and from work by car or taxi. Therefore, the surging number of cars in a narrow street may result in traffic congestion during the rush hour. To solve this problem,\nadequate capital\nis supposed to be allocated on road development to improve inhabitants\' commuting efficiency.\nOther than roads,\nrailways\nshould also\nbe constructed\n, aiming for the increase of\nconsiderable economic profits\n. Since the load capacity of the railway is much larger than that of the road, especially for the transportation of some important supplies such as coal, steel and wood, delivery efficiency would be greatly improved. Apart from that, the railway is more convenient for those visitors from remote regions or other cities. By shortening the hours on the road, people are more able to spend their free time on holiday, which may\nfacilitate the development\nin some developing cities. Therefore, more earnings from tourism might\nstimulate the local economy\n.\nIn conclusion, I believe that money should be spent on both roads and railways taking into consideration\ntheir social impacts and economic values.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (38, 2, 'Environment', 9.0, 'Recycling\nhas been concerned as', NULL, NULL, 'Recycling\nhas been concerned as\nan effective means of improving the environment in a long time, whereas it now seems that domestic waste has not been\nrecycled adequately\n. From my perspective,\nlegislations are necessary\nto encourage waste recycling, but it is by no means the only way to tackle this problem.\nUndeniably, by\nenforcing the environment laws\n, residents would be compelled to recycle their household waste. In this case, there will be punishments for people, ranging from fines to community services. On this account, people are able to\nbuild a strong awareness\nof recycling. Such improved behaviour of the public are\nconducive to\nbuilding a waste-free living environment.\nHowever, compulsory regulations may not be able to\nconvert people\'s lifestyle\nto an eco-friendly one completely, which means that citizens might, occasionally, neglect to do so. In fact, the difficulty in categorizing different types of garbage makes it hard for people to obey the policy strictly all the time. Government has to educate their citizens on this issue.\nIn view of the facts mentioned above, I believe that governments should adopt more measures rather than enacting the laws simply. Compared with punishments, relevant education, the centre of the recycling scheme, might be more effective. For instance, children should be offered lectures on recycling in school. Meanwhile, householders need to be informed of the adverse impacts of disposing of domestic waste carelessly. In addition, more user-friendly recycling facilities and systems are vital to the success of this campaign regardless of whether dwellers could categorize them properly.\nIn conclusion, legal requirements are indeed indispensable for the society to accomplish the environmental goal, the foregoing measures are also supposed to be adopted.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (39, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Many may say, and I agree, that today\'s society has almost\nerased', NULL, NULL, 'Many may say, and I agree, that today\'s society has almost\nerased\nall its boarders and soon will become limitless in what concerns travelling for both work and pleasure. Therefore, if this is to happen, then learning a new language is necessary.\nNowadays, learning a new language for the purpose of working in other countries seems to become more and more popular. Adults in need of money or, why not, recognision are trying to\npursue their happiness\nfar away from home. Also, the  days of employers looking only for capable people have gone. It seems that today\'s employers are looking not only for multi-skilled employees, but they also want people who know more than their mother tongue. Sooner or later, those who omitted learning more are prone to become jobless.\nHowever, to my mind, a new language shouldn\'t be learned just for travelling or working in a foreign country. A foreign language should help the learner broaden his mind. By this I mean that the new language should and will allow us to understand more about the world itself, and maybe our ancestors\' ways of thinking and acting. Needless to say, knowing another language will help us when it comes to understanding the human race, because language is the first poem of a country.\nAll of this being said, I believe that learning a different language should be not only for satisfying our\nphysical needs\n, like money, but also our moral needs, because never before had such\na big thirst for knowledge\nbeen displayed.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (40, 2, 'Government', 9.0, 'Many governments\nplace a high value on', NULL, NULL, 'Many governments\nplace a high value on\nthe development of economy and think it is the most important goal for them, while others argue that other aspects of advancement are as considerable as economic progress. In my point of view, a country will not be prosperous for a long time if the government\nfocuses exclusively on\nthe economy.\nThe importance of developing economy cannot be neglected for every country because it is a fundamental indicator to\nmeasure a nation\'s strength\n. A country that has more fiscal revenues is able to allocate sufficient capital for advancement in some fields, such as the construction of infrastructure, so that the residents can enjoy a more convenient daily life because of efficient public transport and high-quality health care services. In addition, with the economic boom, there will be more job opportunities provided by government, enterprises and small business owners, so that the unemployment rate is able to be lowered markedly, which is helpful to improve people\'s well-being.\nHowever, a country\'s progress has never been about promoting the economic growth only. It also includes a series of other forms of progress. Specifically, governments should also\nput great emphasis on\nthe areas of culture and art. People\'s life could be enriched by visiting different forms of museums or galleries, by which the nation\'s history and traditional culture can be\npreserved and spread\n. Besides, it is undeniable that the scientific and technological improvement can, to a great extent, provide the residents with a more convenient life. Taking the invention of computers as example, the working efficiency can be increased by utilizing office software on those high-tech devices. Therefore, the investment on science and technology is also crucial.\nAccording to the opinions mentioned above, I do believe that the development of countries cannot be confined to economic growth. Other aspects, like culture and technology, are needed to be promoted simultaneously.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (41, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'One important stage in a child\'s growth is\ncertainly the development of', NULL, NULL, 'One important stage in a child\'s growth is\ncertainly the development of\na conscience, which is linked to the ability to tell right from wrong. This skill\ncomes with\ntime and good parenting, and my firm conviction is that punishment does not have much of a role to play in this. Therefore I have to disagree almost entirely with the given statement.\nTo some extent the question depends on the age of the child. To punish a very young child is both wrong and foolish, as an infant will not understand what is happening or why he or she is being punished. Once the age of reason is reached however, a child can be rewarded for good behaviour and\ndiscouraged from\nbad. This kind but firm approach will achieve more than harsh punishments, which might\nentail\nmany negative consequences\nunintended by\nthe parents. To help a child learn the difference between right and wrong, teachers and parents should firstly provide good role modelling in their own behaviour. After that, if sanctions are needed, the punishment should not be of a physical nature, as that\nmerely sends the message\nthat it is acceptable for larger people to hit smaller ones - an outcome which may well result in the child starting to bully others. Nor should the punishment be in any way cruel.\nRather, teachers and parents can use a variety of methods to discipline their young charges, such as detention, withdrawal of privileges, and time-out.\nMaking the punishment fit the crime\nis a useful notion, which would see children being made to pick up rubbish they have dropped, clean up graffiti they have drawn, or apologise to someone they have hurt. In these ways responsibility is developed in the child, which leads to much better future behaviour than does punishment.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (42, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Universities are normally seen as a place where students can learn advanced knowledge and\nimprove employability', NULL, NULL, 'Universities are normally seen as a place where students can learn advanced knowledge and\nimprove employability\n. It is therefore controversial whether undergraduates should study the courses that can be used in a future career, or instead, choose the subjects they have interest in. In my opinion, college students should study useful knowledge that are related to their future.\nSome educationists advocate that students should study whatever they like in university, which may help them to become lifelong learners. By studying the subjects they like, undergraduates might be willing to pay more effort instead of passive learning. Therefore, it is likely for them to continue acquiring knowledge in those fields even after graduation, which contributes to their lifelong learning.\nHowever, other people encourage students to learn practical subjects such as science and technology in universities because they are more likely to find decent jobs after graduation on account of such knowledge. It is widely known that more emerging job opportunities appear in the industries of artificial intelligence, biotechnology and engineering, which are all closely related to information technology. If college students can master grounding knowledge in these fields, they will become more competitive with required qualifications compared with peers.\nFrom my perspective, university students should still major in some useful subjects in order to\nimprove national overall competitiveness\n. Initially, if young adults are proficient in science and technology, they may\nactively participate\nin international competitions that are mostly about mathematics, innovation and technology. In this case, those graduates are expected to rank the top on behalf of their nations. In addition to that, practical subjects are more likely to\nequip students with\nthe ability in\naddressing international issues\nsuch as poverty and epidemic, which results from their solid understanding of natural science courses.\nIn conclusion, undergraduates are supposed to study the subjects that can be used in practice for\nindividual pursuit and national competitiveness.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (43, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'It is said that countries are becoming similar to each other because of the global spread of the same products, which are now available for purchase almost anywhere. I strongly believe that this modern development\nis largely detrimental to', NULL, NULL, 'It is said that countries are becoming similar to each other because of the global spread of the same products, which are now available for purchase almost anywhere. I strongly believe that this modern development\nis largely detrimental to\nculture and traditions worldwide.\nA country\'s history, language and ethos\nare all inextricably bound\nup in\nits manufactured artefacts. If the relentless advance of international brands into every corner of the world continues, these bland packages might one day\ncompletely oust\nthe traditional objects of a nation, which would be a loss of richness and diversity in the world, as well as the sad\ndisappearance of\nthe manifestations of a place\'s character. What would a Japanese tea ceremony be without its specially crafted teapot, or a Fijian kava ritual without its bowl made from a certain type of tree bark?\nLet us not forget either that traditional products, whether these be medicines, cosmetics, toys, clothes, utensils or food, provide employment for local people. The spread of multinational products can often\nbring in its wake\na loss of jobs, as people turn to buying the new brand, perhaps thinking it more glamorous than the one they are used to. This eventually\nputs\nold-school craftspeople\nout of work\n. Finally, tourism numbers may also be affected, as travellers\nbecome disillusioned with\nfinding every place just the same as the one they visited previously. To see the same products in shops the world over is boring, and does not impel visitors to open their wallets in the same way that trinkets or souvenirs unique to the particular area do.\nSome may argue that all people\nare entitled to\nhave access to the same products, but I say that local\nobjects suit local conditions best, and that faceless uniformity worldwide is an unwelcome and\ndreary\nprospect\n.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (44, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Museums are educational places that are important for\ntransmitting knowledge and culture', NULL, NULL, 'Museums are educational places that are important for\ntransmitting knowledge and culture\n. Some museums\nremove admission charges\nin order to benefit the public while others are not free for visitors. In my point of view, paying the entrance fees could bring more benefits than demerits.\nIt is undeniable that charging admission fees would lead to detrimental impacts on museums as it is the place for cultural education. For example, people who cannot afford the tickets would not be permitted to get into the museum, even if they showed great interests in arts and exhibitions. Besides, the majority of people are usually sensitive about admission. They might\nhold a view\nthat museums as public facilities shall be free and therefore once admission is charged, they are probably not willing to visit museums anymore. However, despite the drawbacks mentioned above, there are more benefits of charging entrance fees.\nInitially,\nthe heavy burden\nof governments could, to some extent, be\nrelieved\nif they are not responsible for providing the museums with financial support. Incomes from the sales of museum tickets could effectively\ncover the operation costs\n, such as personnel costs, electricity and water bills. Further, the remaining revenues could be\nallocated\nto employ more professionals and purchase\nadvanced facilities\nto upgrade government services. For example, holding theme exhibitions regularly with delicate artworks and guide services are able to attract more visitors. As a result, the museum can gain more profits as visitors are willing to pay higher tickets for those extra services.\nIn conclusion, although charging the citizens does bring about some adverse effects on the low-income groups, I am convinced that the admission fees could help the museums to\nmaximize their values\nin the long term.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (45, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Traditionally, children have begun studying foreign languages at secondary school, but introducing them earlier is recommended by some educationalists. This policy has been adopted by some educational authorities or individual schools, with both positive and negative outcomes.\nThe obvious argument in its favour is that young children', NULL, NULL, 'Traditionally, children have begun studying foreign languages at secondary school, but introducing them earlier is recommended by some educationalists. This policy has been adopted by some educational authorities or individual schools, with both positive and negative outcomes.\nThe obvious argument in its favour is that young children\npick up\nlanguages much more easily than teenagers. Their brains are still programmed to acquire their mother tongue, which\nfacilitates learning\nanother language, and unlike adolescents, they\nare not inhibited by\nself-consciousness. The greater flexibility of the primary timetable allows for more frequent, shorter sessions and for a play-centred approach, thus\nmaintaining learners\' enthusiasm and progress\n. Their command of the language in later life will benefit from this early exposure, while learning other languages subsequently will be easier for them. They may also gain a better understanding of other cultures.\nThere are, however, some disadvantages. Primary school teachers are generalists, and may not have the necessary language skills themselves. If specialists have to be brought in to deliver these sessions, the flexibility referred to above is diminished. If primary language teaching is not standardised, secondary schools could be faced with a great variety of levels in different languages within their intake, resulting in a classroom experience which\nundoes\nthe earlier gains. There is no advantage if enthusiastic primary pupils become demotivated as soon as they change schools. However, these issues can\nbe addressed strategically\nwithin the policy adopted.\nAnything which encourages language learning benefits society culturally and economically, and early exposure to language learning contributes to this. Young children\'s innate abilities should\nbe harnessed\nto make these benefits more achievable.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (46, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'It has been suggested that high school students should\nbe involved in', NULL, NULL, 'It has been suggested that high school students should\nbe involved in\nunpaid community services as a compulsory part of high school programmes. Most of the colleges are already providing opportunities to gain work experience, however these are not\ncompulsory\n. In my opinion, sending students to work in community services is a good idea as it can provide them with many lots of valuable skills.\nLife skills are very important and by doing voluntary work, students can learn how to communicate with others and work in a team but also how to manage their time and improve their organisational skills. Nowadays, unfortunately, teenagers do not have many after-school activities. After-school clubs are no longer that popular and students mostly go home and sit in front of the TV, browse internet or play video games. By giving them compulsory work activities with charitable or community organisations, they will be encouraged to do something more creative. Skills gained through compulsory work will\nnot only be an asset on\ntheir CV but also\nincrease their employability\n. Students will also gain more respect towards work and money as they will realise that it is not that easy to earn them and hopefully will learn to spend them in a more practical way.Healthy life balance and exercise\nare strongly promoted by\nthe NH, and therefore any kind of spare time charity work will\nprevent from\nsitting and doing nothing. It could also possibly reduce the crime level in the high school age group. If students have activities to do, they will not be bored and come up with silly ideas which can be dangerous for them or their surroundings.\nIn conclusion, I think this is a very good idea, and I hope this programme will\nbe put into action\nfor high\nschools/colleges shortly.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (47, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'A problem of modern societies is\nthe declining level of', NULL, NULL, 'A problem of modern societies is\nthe declining level of\nhealth in the general population,\nwith conflicting views on\nhow to tackle this worrying trend. One possible solution is to provide more sports facilities to encourage a more active lifestyle.\nAdvocates of this believe that today\'s sedentary lifestyle and stressful working conditions mean that physical activity is no longer part of either our work or our leisure time. If there were easy-to-reach local sports centres, we would be more likely to make exercise a regular part of our lives, rather than just\ncollapsing in front of\na screen every evening. The variety of sports that could be offered would\ncater for\nall ages, levels of fitness and interests: those with painful memories of PE at school might be happier in the swimming pool than on the football pitch.\nHowever, there may be better ways of\ntackling\nthis problem. Interest in sport is not universal, and additional facilities might simply attract the already fit, not those who most need them. Physical activity could be encouraged\nrelatively cheaply\n, for example by installing exercise equipment in parks, as my local council has done. This\nhas the added benefit\nthat parents and children often use them together just for fun, which develops a positive attitude to exercise at an early age.\nAs well as physical activity, high tax penalties could\nbe imposed on\nhigh-fat food products, tobacco and alcohol, as excessive consumption of any of these contributes to poor health. Even improving public transport would help: it takes longer to walk to the bus stop than to the car.\nIn my opinion, focusing on sports facilities is too narrow an approach and would not have the desired results. People should be encouraged not only to be more physically active but also to adopt a healthier lifestyle in general.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (48, 2, 'Culture', 9.0, 'It has been reported that several kinds of languages become extinct in recent years. Some people believe that the extinction of some languages will bring a great deal of convenience to people\'s life. From my point of view, this trend does\nbring a series of merits', NULL, NULL, 'It has been reported that several kinds of languages become extinct in recent years. Some people believe that the extinction of some languages will bring a great deal of convenience to people\'s life. From my point of view, this trend does\nbring a series of merits\n.\nA reduction in diversity of languages or dialects, to some extent, can make people\'s work and study easier. Initially, there are general language difficulties among staff in some enterprises that involve transnational business, which might result in greater operating costs and lower work efficiency. With the simplification and unification of languages, direct communication between them is able to\nbring greater efficiency\nduring work as the process of translation is not needed any more. Besides, language differences\nare often obstacles for\nstudents to study abroad. Their burden of studying\nwould be significantly relieved\nif courses are set based on a familiar language system.\nAdmittedly, languages are not only the tool for communicating but also the symbols of particular cultures.If a language faded away, the culture behind it would exit in a short space of time. However, nowadays, the endangered languages or customs could be recorded by cutting-edge technology, such as video- recordings. People can learn and use those languages from the videos whenever they indeed need them. Thus, speaking a mainstream language\nis more crucial for\npeople\'s daily life. Through this way, language barriers are able to be removed, and there will be fewer misunderstanding or embarrassing conditions.\nIn conclusion, fewer languages existing in the world would be beneficial to all aspects of our life, including work, study and daily life.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (49, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'A child\'s education has never been about learning information and basic skills only. It has always included\nteaching the next generation how to be good members of society. Therefore, this cannot be the responsibility of the parents alone.', NULL, NULL, 'A child\'s education has never been about learning information and basic skills only. It has always included\nteaching the next generation how to be good members of society. Therefore, this cannot be the responsibility of the parents alone.\nIn order to be a good member of any society the individual must respect and obey the rules of their community and share their values. Educating children to understand the need to obey rules and respect others always begins in the home and is widely thought to be the responsibility of parents. They will certainly be the first to help children learn what is important in life, how they are expected to behave and what role they will play in their world.\nHowever, learning to understand and share the value system of a whole society\ncannot be achieved just in\nthe home. Once a child goes to school, they are entering a wider community where teachers and peers will\nhave just as much influence as\ntheir parents do at home. At school, children will experience working and living with people from a whole variety of backgrounds from the wider society. This experience should teach them how to co- operate with each other and how to contribute to the life of their community.\nBut to be a valuable member of any community is not like learning a simple skill. It is something that an individual goes on learning throughout life and it is the responsibility of every member of a society to\ntake responsibility for\nhelping the younger generation to become active and able members of that society.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (50, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'The development of science and technology has greatly influenced people\'s life especially in terms of daily communication. These changes in interaction are believed to be more positive than negative on different\nrelationships.', NULL, NULL, 'The development of science and technology has greatly influenced people\'s life especially in terms of daily communication. These changes in interaction are believed to be more positive than negative on different\nrelationships.\nAdmittedly, the communication approach dominated by technology\nexerts a detrimental influence on\nfamily relationship. That is because it has become a common phenomenon that most family members spend more time on their phones instead of chatting with each other. In this case, less attention might be paid on their families because of the use of electronic devices at home. If this continues, the relationship between couples or generations might be weaker and they may behave less caring.\nHowever, the development of technology contributes to more friendships by\nenlarging the opportunities of\nknowing others. In the past, people used to meet new people nearby, who are mostly their colleagues or classmates. This traditional approach largely limited their social relationships because they were less possible to know people who are far away. Contrastingly, nowadays, people are able to know someone new without the constraints of distance. An example might be when online users join a virtual club, they can be gathered by their shared interest on a certain category. Therefore, those people would\ndiscuss related topics\nor even similar life beliefs in further talks via the internet, after which they are likely to become friends even though they never meet in person.\nTo conclude, although technological advancement might harm the relationship among close families, the benefit brought by online communicating should not\nbe underestimated\nwith more friends\nemerging in\npeople\'s daily life.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (51, 2, 'Environment', 9.0, 'There is no doubt that traffic and pollution from vehicles have become huge problems, both in cities and on motorways everywhere. Solving these problems is likely to need more than a simple rise in the price of petrol.\nWhile it is undeniable that private car use is one of the main causes of the increase in traffic and pollution, higher fuel costs are unlikely to limit the number of drivers for long. As this policy would also affect the cost of public transport, it would be very unpopular with everyone who needs to travel on the roads. But there are various other measures that', NULL, NULL, 'There is no doubt that traffic and pollution from vehicles have become huge problems, both in cities and on motorways everywhere. Solving these problems is likely to need more than a simple rise in the price of petrol.\nWhile it is undeniable that private car use is one of the main causes of the increase in traffic and pollution, higher fuel costs are unlikely to limit the number of drivers for long. As this policy would also affect the cost of public transport, it would be very unpopular with everyone who needs to travel on the roads. But there are various other measures that\ncould be implemented\nthat would have a huge effect on these problems.\nI think to\ntackle the problem of\npollution, cleaner fuels need to be developed. The technology\nis already available to\nproduce electric cars that would be both quieter and cleaner to use. Persuading manufacturers and travellers to adopt this new technology would be a more effective strategy for improving air quality, especially in cities.\nHowever, traffic congestion will not be solved by changing the type of private vehicle people can use. To do this, we need to improve the choice of public transport services available to travellers. For example, if sufficient sky trains and underground train systems were built and\neffectively maintained\nin our major cities, then traffic on the roads would\nbe dramatically reduced\n. Long-distance train and coach services should be made attractive and affordable alternatives to driving your own car for long journeys.\nIn conclusion, I think that long-term traffic and pollution reductions would depend on educating the public to use public transport more, and on governments using public money to\nconstruct and run efficient systems\n.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (52, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Being healthy is one of the primary pursuits for individuals. However, more and more people suffer from obesity and health problems in some countries. In order to alleviate this problem, causes of this should be\nascertained', NULL, NULL, 'Being healthy is one of the primary pursuits for individuals. However, more and more people suffer from obesity and health problems in some countries. In order to alleviate this problem, causes of this should be\nascertained\nfirstly and corresponding solutions need to be adopted.\nAlthough a number of factors\nmight be responsible for\nthe decreasing level of health and fitness, high calories intake and lack of exercise, in my opinion, are\nthe crucial ones of\npotential health problems. To be more specific, nowadays, people have too much high-calorie food, such as fast food, instant food and sugary drinks. These kinds of junk food generally are high in calories but low in nutritional value, which are highly possible to cause a weight problem. In addition, health deterioration can\nbe attributed to\na sedentary lifestyle. After school or work, people would prefer to sit on the couch watching TV or killing time with electronic devices, rather than playing outside or taking exercises. With the intake of excessive energy, most of them are in a low state of health unconsciously.\nSpecific measures should be taken for tackling the problems mentioned above. On the one hand, residents need to balance their diet. In order to encourage dwellers to eat healthier, governments could consider increasing taxation on processed food. If people are unwilling to pay higher prices for those, they would be likely to take more fruits and vegetables that contain essential and sufficient vitamins but low in calories. Besides, the public awareness of the importance of physical exercises needs to be\nenhanced\n. Some famous stars with a good shape of body could introduce their fitness habits to the public via television or other forms of media, so that audiences are probably\nmotivated to\njoin some exercise programmes by following these idols.\nIn conclusion, the causes of this social phenomenon are clear, mainly due to people\'s unhealthy diet and shortage of exercise. Each individual should make effort to improve their health conditions by adopting a healthier lifestyle.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (53, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'The relative importance of natural talent and training is a frequent topic of discussion when people try to explain different levels of ability in, for example, sport, art or music.\nObviously, education systems are based on the belief that all children can effectively be taught to', NULL, NULL, 'The relative importance of natural talent and training is a frequent topic of discussion when people try to explain different levels of ability in, for example, sport, art or music.\nObviously, education systems are based on the belief that all children can effectively be taught to\nacquire different skills\n, including those associated with sport, art or music. So from our own school experience, we can find plenty of evidence to support the view that a child can acquire these skills with continued teaching and guided practice.\nHowever, some people believe that\ninnate\ntalent is what differentiates a person who has been trained to play a sport or an instrument, from those who become good players. In other words, there is more to the skill than a learned technique, and this extra talent cannot be taught, no matter how good the teacher or how frequently a child practices.\nI personally think that some people do have talents that are probably\ninherited via their genes\n. Such talents can give individuals a facility for certain skills that allow them to excel, while more hard-working students never manage to reach a comparable level. But, as with all questions of nature versus nurture, they are not mutually exclusive. Good musicians or artists and exceptional sports stars have probably succeeded because of both good training and natural talent. Without the natural talent, continuous training would be neither attractive nor productive, and without the training, the child would not learn how to\nexploit and develop their talent\n.\nIn conclusion, I agree that any child can be taught particular skills, but to be really good in areas such as music, art or sport, then some natural talent is required.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (54, 2, 'Crime', 9.0, 'Fixing punishments for each type of crime has been a debatable issue. There are many arguments supporting both views, those for and those against fixed punishments.\nOn the one hand, fixed punishments will have a deterring effect on society. Individuals knowing that they will be subject to a certain punishment if they are convicted with a given crime, will reconsider committing this act in the first place. This deterring effect also leads to', NULL, NULL, 'Fixing punishments for each type of crime has been a debatable issue. There are many arguments supporting both views, those for and those against fixed punishments.\nOn the one hand, fixed punishments will have a deterring effect on society. Individuals knowing that they will be subject to a certain punishment if they are convicted with a given crime, will reconsider committing this act in the first place. This deterring effect also leads to\nsocial stability\nand security, through\nminimising the number of crimes committed\n. If people knew they would be able to convince the court or the jury of a reason for having committed the crime they are accused of, penal decisions would be largely arbitrary. This would result into criminals getting away with their crimes and into a high level of injustice caused by the subjective approach of different courts.\nOn the other hand,\ntaking\nthe circumstances of a crime and its motivation\ninto consideration\nis a prerequisite for establishing and ensuring justice and equity. A person killing in self-defense cannot be compared to a serial killer, moving from one victim to the next. In my opinion an intermediary position between both solutions is the perfect way to\nestablish and ensure justice and equity\n. There have to be fixed punishments for all crimes. However, criminal laws have to provide for a minimum and a maximum for the punishment and the laws also have to foresee certain cases of\nexemptions\n. An example for setting minimum and maximum penalties is Competition Law where a person being held liable of a crime under this law will be convicted to pay a fine, according to the harm caused by the violation and the profit gained by the violator through committing the crime.\nAs for the exemptions, in some countries the law exempts thiefs stealing food during a period of famine taking into consideration the\ndistress\nand hunger. Also, a person killing in self-defense will be exempted from punishment.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (55, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Nowadays many adults have full-time jobs and the proportion of their lives spent doing such jobs is very high. So feelings about one\'s job must reflect how an individual feels about his or her life as a whole, and because of this, job satisfaction is indeed very important for the wellbeing of that person.\nEmployees get job satisfaction in a number of ways. Firstly, a person needs to feel that they are doing valued and valuable work, so positive feedback from superiors is very important in this respect. A sense of fulfilment is also encouraged if a worker feels the job is worth doing because it contributes to the society or the economy as a whole. Secondly, when someone feels they are improving or', NULL, NULL, 'Nowadays many adults have full-time jobs and the proportion of their lives spent doing such jobs is very high. So feelings about one\'s job must reflect how an individual feels about his or her life as a whole, and because of this, job satisfaction is indeed very important for the wellbeing of that person.\nEmployees get job satisfaction in a number of ways. Firstly, a person needs to feel that they are doing valued and valuable work, so positive feedback from superiors is very important in this respect. A sense of fulfilment is also encouraged if a worker feels the job is worth doing because it contributes to the society or the economy as a whole. Secondly, when someone feels they are improving or\ndeveloping their skills\nthrough training opportunities, for example, then there is a sense of progression and purpose that rewards a worker. The\nsense of belonging\nto a team or a working community also contributes to job satisfaction because colleagues help each other to enjoy their working lives. Satisfaction is also increased by a sense\nof responsibility for and loyalty to a team.\nOf course not everyone enjoys their work. Hard economic realities mean that many people have little choice in the kind of job they can get. In some cases an employee is working in a job that\nsuits\nneither their skills\nnor their personality\n. Some jobs are repetitive and boring, and labour relations may be poor and lead to resentment and insecurity rather than to job satisfaction.\nHowever, even though it is unlikely that all workers do feel happy in their work, I think it is not unrealistic to\npromote more job satisfaction\nin any job. If the factors identified above are\nimplemented\n, then any job can be improved and more workers can feel greater degrees of job satisfaction.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (56, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'There has always been an ongoing debate on universities’ role, such as the bridge to employment and the access to the knowledge. In my view, a university is seen as a place where students\npursue higher education', NULL, NULL, 'There has always been an ongoing debate on universities’ role, such as the bridge to employment and the access to the knowledge. In my view, a university is seen as a place where students\npursue higher education\nin order to prepare for their future career.\nAdmittedly, compared to what has been learned in high school, a university is a place for deeper academic goals. With more opportunities to educational resources such as professional tutors and cutting-edge research, university students are more likely to\ngain more advanced knowledge\ncompared with those compulsory subjects learned in high school. These teaching contents can, therefore help students explore the subjects\nfrom an in-depth perspective\n. However, the theoretical knowledge acquired is not useful until it is applied to a\npractical context\n, which is normally regarded as the future career. If graduates cannot practice what they have learned in real life afterward, they may forget this expertise sooner or later.\nIn fact, universities have functioned as the places for graduates to improve their employability. It is a fact that most young adults will participate in social life after graduation, to support their families or to\nachieve their ambition\n, all of which are based on finding a decent job. Universities,  places where students spend four years, are responsible for their following development by providing support such as basic professional knowledge and career planning skills. In this manner, graduates are\nequipped with the required capabilities\nto apply for their target jobs with more competitive advantages.\nIn conclusion, universities should mainly focus on their aim for a higher employment rate, which means more graduates might find satisfying jobs after college.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (57, 2, 'Media & Technology', 9.0, 'Nowadays, there are lots of advertisements on television or on the streets. Some people think that the advertising\nboosts the sales of goods', NULL, NULL, 'Nowadays, there are lots of advertisements on television or on the streets. Some people think that the advertising\nboosts the sales of goods\nand it encourages people to buy things unnecessarily. This arguments may be true. In my country, many advertising companies produce advertisements with famous and popular actors or singers. People, especially youngsters, buy goods that their favourite singer advertise, although they do not really need the products.\nAlso, on the television screen, a product may look gorgeous and good quality. As a result of it, people often buy goods without enough consideration. Consumers may not actually need it but they buy goods\nimpulsively\nsoon after they watch the advertising. Furthermore, as many customers buy a particular product due to its advertising campaign, the other people may be\naffected by the trend\n, even if the product is not of the real needs of the society.\nOn the other hand, there are various aspects against these arguments. Moreover, it is people\'s choice to make a decision to buy goods. Advertising may be not a cause of customers buying habits. Individuals have their own spending habits. If they have got enough disposable income, then the right to make a decision is given to them. No one actually can judge whether the goods sold are the real needs of the society or not.\nIn addition, as there should be a limited amount of disposable income consumers are able to spend, people try to\nallocate their budgets\n. They cannot be simply\nswayed\nby those advertisements. In conclusion, as customers have their own strong opinions and standard of good quality goods, it is better to leave them to make their own decision in buy goods. It is fairly difficult to say everyone is swayed by advertising and buy good impulsively. However, in sensitive area of businesses such as toy industries, it may be necessary to band advertising to those children as children have not got enough ability to control themselves or to know what they need.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (58, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'As a result of constant media attention, sports professionals in my country have become stars and celebrities, and those at the top are paid huge salaries. Just like movie stars, they live\nextravagant lifestyles', NULL, NULL, 'As a result of constant media attention, sports professionals in my country have become stars and celebrities, and those at the top are paid huge salaries. Just like movie stars, they live\nextravagant lifestyles\nwith huge houses and cars.\nMany people find their rewards unfair, especially when comparing these super salaries with those of top surgeons or research scientists, or even leading politicians who have the responsibility of governing the country. However, sports salaries are not determined by considering the contribution to society a person makes, or the level of\nresponsibility he or she holds\n. Instead, they\nreflect the public popularity of\nsport in general and the level of public support that successful stars can\ngenerate\n. So the notion of \'fairness\' is not the issue.\nThose who feel that sports stars\' salaries are justified might argue that the number of professionals with real talent are very few, and the money is\na recognition of the skills and dedication\na person needs to be successful. Competition is constant and a player is tested every time they perform in their relatively short career. The pressure from the media is intense and there is little privacy out of the spotlight. So all of these factors may justify the huge earnings.\nPersonally, I think that the amount of money such sports stars make is more justified than the huge earnings of movie stars, but at the same time, it indicates that our society\nplaces more value on\nsport than on more essential professions and achievements.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (59, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'In modern society, more and more people have enough savings that allows them to travel in foreign countries. There are different thoughts about whether visitors should follow the traditions and behaviour of the host country. From my own perspective, both host countries and tourists should accept culture differences.\nOn the one hand, if people could', NULL, NULL, 'In modern society, more and more people have enough savings that allows them to travel in foreign countries. There are different thoughts about whether visitors should follow the traditions and behaviour of the host country. From my own perspective, both host countries and tourists should accept culture differences.\nOn the one hand, if people could\ncomply with\nthe local conventions of regions wherever they visit, it will be a way to show their respects and amities. For example, Indians do not eat beef, as they treat the cow as a deity. People who visit there should know and follow this tradition, they would not be welcomed by local residents otherwise. In addition, nowadays, not only do people consider travelling overseas as a chance to relax but they also think it is a way to have self-improvement. Therefore, it is a precious opportunity for tourists to experience foreign cultures by trying new things, such as traditional cuisine, exotic rituals.\nHowever, it might be hard for tourists to follow\na series of customs\nin the host country, because those may be completely different from their own areas. If people are welcomed despite the cultural differences, they would feel more pleasant during the trip and may be willing to revisit it. As a result, the tourism industry could\nthrive\nwith the increasing number of visitors. Moreover, cultural differences brought by foreigners are able to help the local dwellers learn about some unfamiliar customs, which can\nenrich their lives\nand\nbroaden their views\n.\nAs far as I am concerned, it is beneficial for both visitors and locals to accept cultural differences. This kind of experience\nis conducive to\nenriching their knowledge and making friends from the other regions of the world. Thus, the host countries should allow tourists to bring their customs in order to improve\ncultural diversity\n. Meanwhile, visitors should be familiar with and respect the basic local traditions, which must be complied, especially that related to religion.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (60, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Over the last half century the pace of change in the life of human beings has increased beyond our wildest expectations. This has been driven by technological and scientific breakthroughs that are changing the whole way we view the world on an almost daily basis. This means that change is not always a personal option, but an\ninescapable fact', NULL, NULL, 'Over the last half century the pace of change in the life of human beings has increased beyond our wildest expectations. This has been driven by technological and scientific breakthroughs that are changing the whole way we view the world on an almost daily basis. This means that change is not always a personal option, but an\ninescapable fact\nof life, and we need to constantly adapt to keep pace with it.\nThose people who believe they have achieved some security by doing the same, familiar things are\nliving in denial\n. Even when people believe they are\nresisting change\nthemselves, they cannot stop the world around them from changing. Sooner or later they will find that the familiar jobs no longer exist, or that the safe patterns of behaviour are no longer appropriate.\nHowever, reaching the conclusion that change is inevitable is not the same as assuming that \'change is always for the better. Unfortunately, it is not always the case that new things are promoted because they have good impacts for the majority of people. A lot of innovations are made with the aim of making money for a few. This is because it is the rich and powerful people in our society who are able to\nimpose changes\n(such as in working conditions or property developments) that are in their own interests.\nIn conclusion, I would say that change can be\nstimulating\nand\nenergising\nfor individuals when they pursue it themselves, but that all change, including that which is imposed on people, does not necessarily have good\noutcomes.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (61, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Universities are commonly seen as a place where students receive higher education in a specific major. These academic institutions should\nprovide equal educational opportunities', NULL, NULL, 'Universities are commonly seen as a place where students receive higher education in a specific major. These academic institutions should\nprovide equal educational opportunities\nfor students without gender limits, although some particular subjects might\nbe more appropriate\nto male or female candidates.\nIt is undeniable that some subjects are specifically suitable for a certain gender group. For example, subjects such as engineering and astronomy might be more favorable to male graduates, who might be more talented in data analysis and spatial imagination compared with girls. On the contrary, some female students would choose linguistics and literature as their university major because they may be more sensitive with language and better at expression.\nHowever, these compatibilities should not be the excuse for some universities which\ninhibit students from\nchoosing courses based on their preferences. Instead, a university should guide students to\norient\nthemselves in the future career by respecting their decisions. Accepting students regardless of their gender is also in line with the promotion of educational equity. Apart from\nadvocating the standpoint\nthat students of all social classes should have equal rights to education, respecting their gender is also included in education fairness. Suppose college discriminates certain gender by restricting their entrance to university. In that case, those rejected young adults might become disappointed with their future study, or even worse, lose interests in academic field and then quit school. These situations might not be expected by educationists whose aim is to popularize education for all groups; therefore, the equity in teaching and learning might be achieved if there is no gender difference in subject choice.\nIn conclusion, university administrators are supposed to\nimplement educational equity\nby accepting an equal number of male and female students in most subjects.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (62, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'It is quite common these days for young people in many countries to have a break from studying after graduating from high school. The trend is not restricted to rich students who have the money to travel, but is also evident among poorer students who choose to work and\nbecome economically independent', NULL, NULL, 'It is quite common these days for young people in many countries to have a break from studying after graduating from high school. The trend is not restricted to rich students who have the money to travel, but is also evident among poorer students who choose to work and\nbecome economically independent\nfor a period of time.\nThe reasons for this trend may involve the recognition that a young adult who passes directly from school to university is rather restricted in terms of general knowledge and experience of the world. By contrast, those who have spent some time earning a living or travelling to other places, have a broader view of life and better personal resources to\ndraw on\n. They tend to be more independent, which is a very important factor in academic study and research, as well as giving them an advantage in terms of\ncoping with\nthe challenges of student life.\nHowever, there are certainly dangers in taking time off at that important age. Young adults may end up never returning to their studies or finding it difficult to\nreadapt to\nan academic environment. They may think that it is better to continue in a particular job, or to do something completely different from a university course. But overall, I think this is less likely today, when academic qualifications are essential for getting a reasonable career.\nMy view is that young people should be encouraged to\nbroaden their horizons\n. That is the best way for them to\nget a clear perspective\nof what they are hoping to do with their lives and why. Students with such a perspective are usually the most effective and motivated ones and taking a year off may be the best way to gain this.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (63, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Education is vitally important for children\'s growth and development. Many children have to\ncompete with', NULL, NULL, 'Education is vitally important for children\'s growth and development. Many children have to\ncompete with\ntheir peers in order to\nsurpass\nothers during their childhood. However, others believe that it is more important for them to learn how to cooperate. Personally, I do agree with the latter.\nOn the one hand, competition skills are beneficial for children to be more adaptable to a highly competitive society. Indeed, the fierce competition starts from primary school where students make great efforts to get better performance in order to acquire praise from their teachers and parents. Therefore, the awareness of competition cultivated from an early age is a crucial factor that could\nimpel the youngsters\nto\nendeavour constantl\ny\nand become excellent adults in the future.\nHowever, besides having the sense of competition, students should make greater efforts to learn how to co-operate with others. Specifically, after they graduate and start their career, they would find the importance of teamwork, since it is impossible for them to complete a project by themselves alone. Admittedly, the\nworking efficiency could be enhanced\nwith cooperation among colleagues. Every individual has his or her own adept skills and weakness, and teamwork means the strength of every team member would be\nutilized\nto\naccomplish their common goal\nwithin the shortest time.\nAccording to what has been mentioned above, the cooperation abilities, in my opinion, are more crucial rather than\nblind competition\n. Children should be taught to work hard instead of striving to be the best all the time. Besides, if they are trained to be good at working with peers since childhood, they could\nintegrate themselves into\ngroup life.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (64, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Today the way we consider human psychology and mental development is\nheavily influenced by', NULL, NULL, 'Today the way we consider human psychology and mental development is\nheavily influenced by\nthe genetic sciences. We now understand the importance of inherited characteristics more than ever before. Yet we are still unable to decide whether an individual\'s personality and development are more influenced by genetic factors (nature) or by the environment (nurture).\nResearch, relating to identical twins, has\nhighlighted\nhow significant inherited characteristics can be for an individual\'s life. But whether these characteristics are able to develop within the personality of an individual surely depends on whether the circumstances allow such a development. It seems that the experiences we have in life are so unpredictable and so powerful, that they can\nboost or over-ride\nother influences, and there seems to be plenty of research findings to confirm this.\nMy own view is that there is no one\nmajor influence\nin a person\'s life. Instead, the traits we inherit from our parents and the situations and experiences that we encounter in life are constantly\ninteracting\n. It is the interaction of the two that\nshapes a person\'s personality\nand dictates how that personality develops. If this were not true, then we would be able to predict the behaviour and character of a person from the moment they were born.\nIn conclusion, I do not think that either nature or nurture is the major influence on a person, but that both have powerful effects. How these factors interact is still unknown today and they remain\nlargely unpredictable\nin a person\'s life.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (65, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'In our daily life, we\ncommunicate information', NULL, NULL, 'In our daily life, we\ncommunicate information\nthrough lots of different media like the internet, televisions, radios, books, cell phones, films etc. All the media for information interchange have advantages and disadvantages and not all can attract all types of audiences. Comics, books, radios, televisions, film and theatre are all very powerful media for communicating information. In my opinion books, televisions and film among those aforementioned six media are most effective.\nBooks are the witness of history and the main source from which we gain knowledge. From a very ancient period till now, books have been working as the light-house for our society. In our childhood, we gather most of our knowledge and skills from books. It\nopens new horizons\nin front of us. The writer writes down their experiences, imaginations, knowledge, explanation etc. about each and every issue of our lives. Books are the long-lasting protocol to make a bridge among writers and readers.\nHowever, all are not happy to read books. They expect something easier and more vivid. Music, radios, films etc. are more\nappealing to\nthem. Television is another powerful media. Watching television is a part of our daily lives. Most of the people who have a TV set, watch programs, news etc. with apt attention. It is a strong medium for Government and other organisations to send their messages to the mass population. Program representatives also\nbroadcast the people\'s view\nand opinions\nabout different controversial issues in TV programs.\nHowever, this medium has lots of\ndemerits\nand bad impacts. Government and politically biased organisations often send negative and misleading news. Again young people watch different satellite channels and try to\nadopt the alien culture\nwhich is really harmful for the culture and tradition of a country.\nFilms are an\naudio-visual representation\nand can\ncatch the attention of\npeople from different geographical locations, races and cultures. A good film can\nshape someone\'s morality and doctrine\nand the film-makers with their huge amount of money, are so careful to make their films realistic and\neye-absorbing\n. Every film has a direct or potential message or moral. On the contrary, some films also bring a wrong message to us. For example, protagonists are always smoking in the films and it seems that smoking is a good and smart habit. It causes many younger people imitate them smoking.\nIn conclusion, I would like to state that books, televisions and films are the most powerful and effective medias for communicating information.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (66, 2, 'Social Life', 9.0, 'Happiness is very difficult to define, because it means so many different things to different people. While some people link happiness to wealth and material success, others think it lies in emotions and loving personal relationships. Yet others think that spiritual paths, rather than either the material world or relationships with people, are the only way to true happiness.\nBecause people', NULL, NULL, 'Happiness is very difficult to define, because it means so many different things to different people. While some people link happiness to wealth and material success, others think it lies in emotions and loving personal relationships. Yet others think that spiritual paths, rather than either the material world or relationships with people, are the only way to true happiness.\nBecause people\ninterpret happiness\nfor themselves in so many different ways, it is difficult to give any definition that is true for everyone. However, if there are different kinds of happiness for different individuals then the first step in achieving it would be to have\na degree of self-knowledge\n. A person needs to know who he or she is before being able to know what it is that makes him or her happy.\nOf course, factors such as loving relationships, good health, the skills to earn a living, and a peaceful environment all contribute to our happiness too. But this does not mean that people without these conditions cannot be happy.\nOverall, I think an ability to keep\nclear perspectives\nin life is a more essential factor in achieving happiness. By that I mean an ability to have a clear sense of what is important in our lives (the welfare of our families, the quality of our relationships, making other people happy, etc.) and what is not (a problem at work, getting annoyed about\ntrivial things\n, etc.). Like self-awareness, this is also very difficult to achieve, but I think these are the two factors that may be the most important for achieving happiness.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (67, 2, 'Government', 9.0, 'Creativity is the mother of innovation. Hence, many creative artists use words, pictures, music, or films as a medium to deliver their ideas and experiences to the audience. It is a point of much debate among different communities that the government should\ncensor the material', NULL, NULL, 'Creativity is the mother of innovation. Hence, many creative artists use words, pictures, music, or films as a medium to deliver their ideas and experiences to the audience. It is a point of much debate among different communities that the government should\ncensor the material\nproduced by artists. Nevertheless, personally, I believe that there should not be any interference from the government so that the creators produce the best content without worrying about limitations.\nThe foremost reason for supporting the above statement is that it allows producers to\nthink beyond the norm\nwhile producing ideas. In other words, it facilitates them to be creative which is essential for a prosperous society. To illustrate, in the past movies used to be of the same type without much variation. Even if they had produced bad content, users still used to watch it because there were not many options available. However, with the invention of online-streaming platforms with no censorship such as Amazon Prime and Netflix, more material related to comedy, crime and action is available and users can choose according to their wishes.\nAdditionally, it is hard to define the criteria to\nrestrict\nthe content because it is subjective. Sometimes, authorities take action only because they find it criticizing. For example, In India, authorities asked the producers to remove some offensive scenes from an Amazon Prime movie just because it was criticizing how the government\nmishandled\nthe pandemic. Thus, in order to make the state and citizens aware of the real issues, there should not be any control.\nIn conclusion, I am inclined to support the freedom of artists in order to produce ideas according to their wishes because it will provide the avenue to be creative and go beyond their limits. Moreover, it will allow authenticated material to\nflow without any limitations\n. The authorities will be forced to work for the welfare of their citizens as they will be more aware of actual issues.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
INSERT INTO `writing_exemplars` VALUES (68, 2, 'Education', 9.0, 'Poor student behaviour seems to be an increasingly widespread problem and I think that modern lifestyles are probably responsible for this.\nIn many countries, the birth rate is decreasing so that families are smaller with fewer children. These children are often spoilt, not in terms of love and attention because working parents do not have the time for this, but', NULL, NULL, 'Poor student behaviour seems to be an increasingly widespread problem and I think that modern lifestyles are probably responsible for this.\nIn many countries, the birth rate is decreasing so that families are smaller with fewer children. These children are often spoilt, not in terms of love and attention because working parents do not have the time for this, but\nin more material ways\n. They are allowed to have whatever they want, regardless of price, and to behave as they please. This means that the children grow up without consideration for others and without any understanding of where their standard of living comes from. When they get to school age they have not learnt any self control or discipline. They have less respect for their teachers and refuse to obey school rules in the way that their parents did.\nTeachers continually complain about this problem and measures should be taken to combat the situation. But I think the solution to the problem\nlies with\nthe families, who need to be more aware of the future consequences of spoiling their children. If they could raise them\nto be considerate of\nothers and to be social, responsible individuals, the whole community would benefit. Perhaps parenting classes are needed to help them to do this, and high quality \' nursery schools could be\nestablished\nthat would support families more in terms of raising the next generation. The government should\nfund\nthis kind of parental support, because this is no longer a problem for individual families, but for society as a whole.', '2026-05-18 14:41:33');
